Commentary.Commentary: The second innings is set to begin! The Australian players stride out to the middle. Followed by Rory Burns and Haseeb Hameed who walk out to bat for England. Mitchell Starc to start with the ball.

Rght then. The visitors have a steep task in front of them. They would hope to remain unscathed till the stumps on Day 2. Australia, on the other hand, would hope to take a couple of wickets and put instant pressure on the tourists. Do join us in a while for a thrilling passage of play.

England bowlers toiled hard for two days straight in this game. There were moments when they thought the game was getting away from them. With a couple dropped catches on the first Day and a few falling short of the slip cordon on Day 2. Only Broad and Stokes got into the wicket’s column on Day 1. The hosts had a lot of wickets to play with on Day 2, and Smith took complete advantage of that. He was scoring at a brisk rate and the Englishmen were forced to change their bowling plans. Robinson was on fire with the ball in the first session and set back a set batter in Labuschagne. While, Root and Stokes chipped in as well, to make the first session theirs. It was Smith and Carey who looked solid in the middle and scored at a brisk rate. But it was Anderson, who weaved his magic and sent back both the set batters, to take the momentum along with them in the Tea Break. The last session was just an insult to injury, the bowlers would’ve liked to chop the tail-enders quickly but took a beating instead.

Declare! Steve Smith has signalled from the pavilion and Australia DECLARE AT 473/9 . It was a steady start by the hosts with the blade. They lost Harris pretty early on. Then it was the third wicket-partnership between Warner and Labuschagne who took the game away from the visitors. Yet again, in the series, Warner slipped out in his 90s and Smith and Labuschagne ended on a high at the end of Day 1, after the latter was dropped at 95. Runs came more swiftly on Day 2, thanks to the tremendous effort of the stand-in skipper, Steven Smith. Marnus Labuschagne came out and was sent back on 103 by Robinson, after getting him caught off a no-ball. Head and Green had a short stay in the middle. Later, Smith and Carey stitched a crucial stand for the sixth wicket of 91 runs, Carey was the aggressor with his maiden Test fifty, but both were sent back by Anderson at the stroke of Tea. Starc came out with Neser in the final session to bat. The pair stitched a quick-fire 58-run stand. The latter though slipped out, Starc then switched gears and made sure his side ends on a high.

Right then! We are into the last session on Day 2 which will be played under the artificial lights! Will the Aussies declare straightaway after Tea? Or will they go hard in the next few overs, get to that 400-run mark and then declare? We will find that out. Do join us for another intriguing session which will begin at 7.30 pm local (9 am GMT).

English bowlers toiled hard in the second session but luck wasn't going their way as there were lot of instances where the ball didn't carry to the slip cordon. The Aussie batters came hard at them in the second session and the tourists had to change some of their bowling plans. It was James Anderson who struck twice and got rid of both Steven Smith and Alex Carey. A total of 88 runs were scored in the second session and England managed to pick a couple of wickets just at the stroke of Tea.

Australia did lose Steven Smith and Alex Carey just at the stroke of Tea but the damage had already been done as the stand-in skipper batted beautifully and was backed up well by Carey who also scored his maiden Test fifty. These two put on a 91-run stand for the sixth wicket and  kept the English bowlers at bay. Australia are in a good position in this game but they would be a touch disappointed as they lost two batters in the 90s in this innings and it was only the second instance in the history of Ashes that two batters were dismissed in the 90s in the same innings. The first instance was in 2006 with Paul Collingwood (96) and Kevin Pietersen (92) which was played in Brisbane.

Just like Day 1, Australia have managed to come back well in the second session after the opening session belonged to the tourists. Australia's stand-in skipper, Steven Smith along with Alex Carey have taken their team to a very good total.

He was a bit sloppy in the field, since the first Test match, but this catch was a crucial one and he does not drop this one. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 2!
Commentary.Howout: c Haseeb Hameed b James Anderson

After every ball, Smith is talking to himself and indicating, okay the ball is moving this way. Okay, the ball is moving that way. The on-air commentators are whispering, "Whom is he talking to?" And suddenly a suggestion comes - "Smith's world is unique. He is his own teacher and his own student. So the teacher is telling the student that the ball moved that way and you should have played it this way. And the student is responding by nodding his head. Normally, this involves two individuals but in Smith's case, he is two in one"

It might just seem a bit intriguing looking at the number of edges that are falling short of the slip cordon today. The slip fielders always mark their position looking at where their keeper is standing. So, is the problem or fault entirely with Jos Buttler? A no and a yes. Why are we sitting on the fence? Let's start with the no then. Just compare the carry on Day 1 and the carry on Day 2. Yesterday, Buttler was getting majority of the balls at chest and shoulder height. Even the one he put down late in the evening, of Labuschagne, was above the waist. So probably, Jos is still thinking - 'Today is just Day 2, so the carry will not go down so much.' Now, this is where we might pin the fault on Buttler. We are already halfway through Day 2 and by now, JB should have realized that the balls are definitely not carrying as highly as on Thursday. So maybe, say from the start of the second session at least, he should have taken a step or two ahead, especially given that England do not have 140kph-plus bowlers in the side. The average pace is around 130-135 and the extra pace, or the lack of it, definitely matters.

A couple of runs now! A length ball, angled into the batter. Carey stays inside the crease, closes the face of the bat and flicks it through square leg for a brace.
Good-length ball, around off. Carey stays on the back foot and pushes it to covers.
A length ball, around middle and off, Carey pushes it away.
Back of a length, around off. Carey punches it to cover.
Short and wide outside off. Smith shuffles across and shoulders his arms. This one turned in with some bounce.
Full and outside off. Smith prods to the pitch of the ball and defends it out.
Floated, outside off. Carey pushes it to point for a single.
Full and around off. Carey drives it to cover. Stokes gets low and stops it from running past him.
Flatter and short, around middle and leg. Smith goes back and punches it through point for a single.
Full and on middle. Smith flicks it to mid-wicket.
Yes, he surely can! This one is quicker, on a good-length, around off, close to the body this time. Carey shoulders his arms at it.
Five dots in a row! Fuller and on leg. Carey tucks it to mid-wicket. Can Anderson gets his tenth maiden of the game?
Good length, on the pads, Carey stays inside the crease and nudges it to mid-wicket.
Length ball, angled across the left-hander on off. Carey defends it out watchfully.
Slightly short, outside off. Carey punches it aggressively towards point, straight to the man there.
A length ball, on off. Carey stays back and pushes it towards cover. Not in the gap though.
Who will start from the opposite end? James Anderson it is.
Flatter, around off, spinning in. Smith goes back and pushes it to cover. Australia with a bright start to the second session.
Drop and run! Tossed up, outside off, Carey leans forward and defends it to cover. Carey scampers through to the other side for a quick single.
Looped up, outside off, turning away. Carey defends it to the left of first slip.
Angled into the pads, Smith goes back and flicks it to fine leg for a single this time.
Tossed up, full and on off. Alex Carey gets low and reverse-sweeps it towards third man for three runs.
Floated, full and on leg. Smith clips it to deep square leg and gets a single.

We are back for the second session! The players of England stride out to the middle and they are followed by Alex Carey and Steven Smith who walk out to bat for Australia. Joe Root to start with the ball.
... Day 2, Session 2 ...

Right then. Something to smile about in the English camp then. Their bowlers will come back after the break and look to bowl out the hosts as quick as possible. Australia, on the flip side, will hope to bat another whole session and assess things at the Tea break. Do join us for another thrilling session of cricket at 5:10 pm local (0640 GMT).

Steven Smith holds the key for his side now! It was Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith who started the day on a good note. The runs were coming in at a good rate for the latter throughout the innings, while the former lost his track and slipped out after a gritty knock of 103. Steven Smith and Travis Head later steadied the ship by not letting the visitors capitalize and racked up runs at a good rate. Head made his intentions clear as he hit one ball over Root for a boundary, but was sent back on the very next delivery as he got deceived by the slowness of the ball. Alos, Green was sent back to the pavilion within a flash, just like his outing in Brisbane. In the end, Carey and Smith made sure they remain unscathed till the break.

A well fought session by the visitors! England could not keep it tight, with a still-new ball on the morning of Day 2. Attacking the stumps should’ve been their aim early on but as they kept leaking runs, their bowlers bowled wide and the batters were not bothered by it at all. Until Ollie Robinson showed his team-mates how its done. He was on the money with the ball in the first session amongst the seamers. He got rid of Marnus Labuschagne in his second attempt, as the first one was ruled out as he overstepped. Robinson got the outside edge into play quite frequently, but a few opportunities fell short of the slip cordon. Soon, Root and Stokes chipped in as well by sending back Head and Green respectively to get their side back in the hunt.

What a session of Test cricket this one was. Roller-coaster of emotions in the English camp, while Marnus Labuschagne rode his luck, but he ran out of it eventually. In the final half-an-hour of play, England picked up wickets in cluster and got their side back into the game.
A bumper, around middle. Alex Carey ducks underneath and that will be Dinner on Day 2!
Stokes follows it up with a pin-point yorker, around off. Alex Carey digs it out watchfully.
Back of a length, down leg. Alex Carey looks to pull but he gets it from the inner half of his blade towards the leg slip fielder.
BEATEN! Good-length delivery, just outside off. Alex Carey looks to poke at it but gets beaten on his outside edge. What a spell this has been from Stokes!
Banged into the deck, around middle. Alex Carey ducks underneath.
Length ball, around leg. Alex Carey misses his nudge on the leg side and gets hit on his pad.
Fuller in length, around middle. Steven Smith blocks it out.
Floated, around off. Alex Carey taps it to backward point and takes off for a quick run.
Loopy ball, around middle. Alex Carey blocks it back to the bowler.
Flatter and quicker, outside off. Alex Carey punches it to extra cover.
Flatter ball, on off. Alex Carey blocks it off the front foot.
Tossed up, outside off. Alex Carey gets down on his knee to paddle it down leg but it goes off the toe end towards mid-wicket.
A yorker, outside off. Steven Smith sits back and squeezes it out towards backward point.
Leg bye! Length ball, around leg. Alex Carey misses his flick and gets hit on his thigh pad. The ball rolls behind square on the leg side for a leg bye.
Short of a length, outside off. Alex Carey punches it to cover.

FOUR! Banged into the deck, around leg. Carey stays back and swivel-pulls it behind square on the leg side. Dawid Malan runs across to his right from fine leg but he fails to stop the boundary. 300 comes up for Australia!
Good-length ball, around middle. Alex Carey looks to defend but he misses and gets hit high on his pad.
Good-length delivery, angling away from the batter. Alex Carey leaves it alone.
Flatter ball, turning down leg. Steven Smith lets it through to the keeper.
Fuller in length, around off. Steven Smith defends it off the front foot.
Loopy ball, around leg. Steven Smith tucks it to mid-wicket.
A quicker ball, fired down leg. Steven Smith lets it be.
Flatter ball, down leg. Steven Smith stays back and nudges it behind square on the leg side for a couple of runs.
Flatter ball, down leg. Steven Smith offers no shot, it hits his pad and the ball goes past the leg slip fielder. The batters don't run though.
Stokes bangs it into the deck, around off. Alex Carey sways away from the line of the delivery.
On a length, around off. Alex Carey blocks it off the front foot.
Back of a length, on middle. Alex Carey turns it to mid-wicket.
Alex Carey comes in at number 7.

OUT! BOWLED! That is a peach of a delivery from Stokes and Cameron Green is castled yet again! Stokes hurls a length ball, angling in from off. The ball straightens and goes past Green's defense to knock his off stump over. Green completely misread the line of the delivery as he played for the inswinger! Top stuff from Ben Stokes. Two wickets in two overs for England and they are back in the contest!
Commentary.Howout: b Ben Stokes

Commentary.Commentary: First runs in the series for Cameron Green! Length ball, angling in from leg. Green glances it towards fine leg and comes back for the second run.
Banged into the deck, around leg. Steven Smith swivels and pulls it behind square on the leg side for a run.
Flatter and quicker, outside off. Cameron Green stays back and leaves it alone.
Tossed up, on a length, around leg. Cameron Green turns it to mid on.
Overpitched ball, on off. Cameron Green digs it out.
Cameron Green is the new man in.

OUT! BOWLED! Joe Root strikes and gets the big wicket of Travis Head! Did him for flight and drift, maybe! Loopy ball, drifting in around leg and then spinning away late. Head looks to flick it across the line but he misses, gets into a tangle and the ball crashes onto his off pole. So the ploy to attack Root hasn't quite worked for Australia! The centurion of the previous game walks back to the hut.
Commentary.Howout: b Joe Root

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Top shot! Loopy ball, on a length, around off. Head smacks it over the bowler's head and bags a boundary.
Tossed up, on off. Travis Head blocks it off the front foot.
Back of a length, outside off. Smith looks to play the upper cut but gets beaten by the bounce. Another good over for the hosts.
Short ball, into the ribs. Head drags his pull shot towards fine leg for a single.
Back of a length, around off. Head blocks it out and the ball lobs in front of him.
Short and on off. Smith pulls it through square leg for a single.

FOUR! EDGED AND OVER! Smith gets his FIFTY in no time. Short ball, around off. The ball is above his head. Smith throws his bat at it and gets an outside edge, as the ball flies over the keeper and into the fine leg fence.
Back of a length, around the hips. Head clips it to square leg and crosses for a single.
Tossed up, full and outside off. Smith comes forward and defends it out with his pads. Runs are coming in at a really good pace for the hosts.
Flatter and on off. Smith gets behind the line and blocks it out.
FOUR! Nicely guided and another boundary for the Australian skipper. Short and wide outside off. Smith hangs on the back foot and guides it through backward point for a boundary.
Darted on the pads, Head clips it to mid-wicket for a single.
Tossed up, full and on off. Head drives it towards cover.
Flighted, full and on off. Smith advances down the track and pushes it to mid off for a single.
Short ball, going down leg. Head shoulders his arms and leaves it alone for the keeper. A decent start by Stokes.
Short ball and on off. Head defends it out to the off side.
Back of a length, on middle and leg. Smith stays on the back foot and pulls it through mid-wicket for a single.
Length and on off. Smith continues to remain solid in his defense.
Full-length ball, on off. Smith blocks it out watchfully.
WIDE! A sharp bumber, going above Smith's head. Umpire calls it as a wide.
FOUR! Up and Over! Ben Stokes sticks with his plan of bowling short, but gets punished this time. Back of a length, outside off. Smith hangs back and lofts it over point for a boundary.
Ben Stokes (13-1-50-1) comes into the attack.
On off, pushed away. A good over by Root.

Full and on off. Head drives it towards mid on. He is out of his crease looking for a single. But Smith is blocked by Root who is ball watching and sends Head back. No trouble for Head, as he gets back safely.

Nice turn and bounce this time! Floated, outside off. The ball turns away with some extra bounce. Head looks to cut it away but the bounce beats him. Jos Buttler collects the ball near his chest and clips the bails off. Head had his back leg planted inside the crease.
Looped up, full and on off. Head prods and blocks itout.
Tossed up, around middle. Head goes back and blocks it back to the bowler.
Floated, full and outside off. Head pushes it out.
Joe Root (11-1-37-0) comes to bowl.
Three leg byes! Touch short and on the pads, Head stays back and misses his flick. It goes towards fine leg off the pads. The batters run three and the umpire signals a leg bye.
Good running this time! A full-length ball, on the pads, Smith clips it through mid-wicket. The batters run three before the fielder cuts it out.
Full length and on off. Smith looks to defend it out. The ball takes the outside edge and goes towards backward point and collects a brace.
Good length, wide outside off. Smith leaves it alone.
Length and on off. Smith keeps it out watchfully.
Full and outside off. Smith leans forward and blocks it out.
FOUR! Crunched! Short and wide, outside off. Head swats it through cover-point and bags a boundary.
NO BALL! Woakes has overstepped and he has to reload the last delivery again. A length ball, outside off. Head drives it to cover.
Full and on leg. Smith clips it to deep square leg for a single.
Nice fielding by Malan. A length ball, around off. Head punches it towards cover. Dawid Malan dives to his left and makes a sharp half-stop. The batters cross for a single.

EDGED! But does not carry again. Woakes comes over the wicket this time. A length ball, angled across the batter. Head looks to push it away but gets an outside edge towards second slip. Rory Burns dives forward but the ball lands in front of him, as Head plays it with soft hands.
Good-length ball, angled in on off. Head stays back and punches it towards point. Hameed gathers it safely.
Full length, on off. Head comes inside and plays it to the left of the bowler. Woakes puts his left hand out and stops the ball.
Another maiden for Ollie Robinson. Full-length ball, angled into the batter. Smith defends it to the leg side.
Length and on off. Smith blocks it out.
Lovely bowling from Ollie Robinson. On a length, on the fourth stump line. Steven Smith shuffles across to play at it, but as the ball curls away late. Smith opts to leave it instead.
Fuller, around off. Smith prods and defends it out solidly.
Good-length ball, in the channel of uncertainty. Smith is persistent on leaving the ball outside his eyeline.
Length ball, outside off. Smith leaves it alone for the keeper.
Good length and on off. Head defends it to point.
A length ball, outside off. Head shoulders his arms at it.
Another dot! Good-length ball, angled into the batter. Head defends it out towards mid on.
Length ball, outside off. Head stays back and cuts it towards point. Not in the gap this time.
Nice timing! Good-length ball, around off. Head hangs back and punches it through the gap at covers and gets a brace.
Woakes comes 'round the wicket. A length ball, just outside off. Head stays back and taps it to point.

DRINKS! England must be a bit relieved side as they finally got to see the back of Marnus Labuschagne and they would now look to chip in with wickets and not let the Aussie batters to pile on the runs. Ollie Robinson is in the middle of a very good spell here and Travis Head and Steven Smith would look to see through this passage of play and then attack later.
Length ball, on off. Smith defends it back to the bowler.
BEATEN! Ollie Robinson is on the money yet again. A length ball, on the fourth stump line. Smith covers his off stump and looks to defend it out but gets beaten on the outside edge.
A full-length ball, on off. Steven Smith defends it out solidly.
A good-length ball, outside off, Smith pushes it to cover.

Enquiry from behind the wickets but the umpire is unmoved! On a length, in the channel of uncertainty. Steven Smith comes across and shoulders his arms. The ball flies of the deck, to clip the thigh pads and go towards the keeper.

SHORT! Good-length ball, around off, nipping away. Steven Smith looks to defend it out, but manages to get an outside edge. The ball goes towards the right of second slip. Rory Burns there dives to his right but the ball lands in front of him.
Length ball, on off. Head defends it out watchfully.
Back of a length, on off. Head hops and blocks it onto the deck.
Length and on off. Head blocks it out watchfully. Not getting carried away with that boundary.
FOUR! Width on offer and Travis Head opens his account with a boundary. Slightly short, outside off. Head stays on the back foot and cuts it through covers for a boundary.
On a length, around off, angled across the left-hander. Travis Head stays back and blocks it out.
Woakes serves a length ball, on the pads. Head stays inside the crease and nudges it to square leg.
Chris Woakes (15-5-36-0) comes into the attack now.
Length ball, around off. Steven Smith gets behind the line of the delivery and pushes it to mid on.

NO BALL! Good-length delivery, around off and curling away late. Steven Smith gets back in his crease to block but he gets squared up yet again and the ball hits him high on his bat. The umpire signals a no ball as Robinson oversteps.
Fuller in length, outside off. Steven Smith presses forward and drives but straight to the mid off fielder.
Good-length ball, on off. Steven Smith blocks it off the front foot.
Length ball, around off. Steven Smith looks to defend but gets squared up and it goes off the outer half of the blade towards point.
Back of a length, outside off and jagging back in late. Steven Smith shoulders his arms to it.
On a length, just outside off. Steven Smith moves across in his crease and leaves it alone.

Leg bye! Good-length delivery, angling in late from middle. Steven Smith mises his flick and the ball ricochets off his thigh pad towards Haseeb Hameed at leg slip who half-stops it and the batters cross for a leg bye.
Length ball, around middle. Steven Smith covers the line of the ball and defends it.
On a length, around off. Steven Smith blocks it out.

FOUR! Another short ball, around leg. Steven Smith stays back, swivels and pulls it behind square on the leg side. Chris Woakes at deep backward square leg does not pick the ball and the ball races away to the fence.
Banged into the deck, around leg. Steven Smith ducks under it.
Good-length ball, around middle. Steven Smith tucks it to the leg side.
Good-length ball, around off. Travis Head blocks it off the back foot. A wicket-maiden from Robinson!
Travis Head comes out at number 5.
Marnus Labuschagne will take the review for LBW! The original decision is OUT. There is no shot involved. The Ball Tracker shows three reds and Marnus Labuschagne finally walks off the field.

OUT! LBW! Ollie Robinson gets his man this time and he is pumped! Joy for England! This was a length ball, jagging back in sharply after pitching from outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it but the ball nips back late and hits him near the knee roll. Robinson appeals and the umpire raises his dreaded finger. Marnus Labuschagne consults with his partner, Steven Smith and opts for a review. The Hawk Eye indicates three reds and Labuschagne is a goner! Robinson would surely breathe a sigh of relief!

Commentary.Commentary: Short of a length, way outside off and curling away late. Marnus Labuschagne shoulders arms to it.
Back of a length, around off. Marnus Labuschagne hangs back and defends it to cover.
Good-length delivery, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne prods but does not offer any shot to this one.
On a length, angling in from outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone.
Back of a length, outside off. Steven Smith leaves it alone.
Short of a length, way outside off. Steven Smith lets it be.

DROPPED! A tough one though! Banged into the deck, around off. Marnus Labuschagne stays back and pulls. Ollie Robinson at square leg hops to his right and stretches out to grab it but he puts it down and the ball goes past him for a run.
Length ball, angling in from middle. Marnus Labuschagne flicks it to square leg.
Good-length ball, on middle. Marnus Labuschagne blocks it out.
Good-length ball, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne stays back to defend it.
Outside off, left alone by Smith. Cricket is a cruel game. Ollie Robinson with a superb over but still he won't be happy about it.
LEG BYE! Fuller, on the pads, Marnus Labuschagne misses his flick. The ball goes to square leg off the pads. A leg bye is collected.
Length, around middle and leg. Marnus Labuschagne nudges it to mid-wicket.
Fuller and on middle. Marnus Labuschagne tucks it to mid-wicket.
Good-length ball, around off. The ball nips away off the deck. Marnus Labuschagne shoulders his arms and lets it go through him.
Full-length ball, on off. Marnus Labuschagne drives it to mid off and yells No RUN.

Is that a no ball? The replays show Ollie Robinson did not have any part of his foot behind the popping line and hence the umpire signals a no ball and Marnus Labuschagne has been called back to bat. Marnus Labuschagne is riding his luck even on Day 2. The English camp is gutted. Ollie Robinson still can't believe it.

NO BALL! Oh, dear! A chance goes begging and Marnus Labuschagne gets a lottery ticket! Ollie Robinson bowls a beauty straightaway, gets the nick and most importantly Jos Buttler takes the catch this time. But Robinson oversteps and the TV umpire confirms that it is a no ball. This was a good-length ball, around the corridor of uncertainty, Marnus Labuschagne looks to block it but gets the thick outside edge towards the keeper. Buttler moves to his right and takes a good catch. The on-field umpire asks Marnus Labuschagne to wait as he checks the front foot of Ollie Robinson. The replays roll in and it suggests that there was nothing behind the line. It is a no ball and the Adelaide crowd erupts. Looks like Christmas came 7 times early for Marnus Labuschagne. The smile on his face as he walks back into the middle says it all.
Ollie Robinson comes into the attack now.
Broad goes fuller this time, around leg. Steven Smith looks to flick but gets in a tangle, loses his balance and gets hit on his pad.
Back of a length, outside off. Steven Smith shoulders arms to this one.
Back of a length, jagging back in sharply from outside off. Steven Smith stays back to block but he misses and gets hit high on his pad. A stifled appeal but the umpire is unmoved.
Another ball, jagging back in down leg. Steven Smith misses his flick yet again.
Good-length delivery, outside off. Steven Smith blocks it to cover-point.
Good-length ball, angling down leg. Steven Smith misses his flick.
Fuller in length, drifting down leg. Marnus Labuschagne clips it past the mid-wicket fielder. The fielder there chases it and the batters take a couple.
Good-length ball, on off. Marnus Labuschagne defends it off the front foot.
On a length, around off and jagging back in late. Marnus Labuschagne looks to leave but gets hit high on his body.

FOUR! Finally, Marnus Labuschagne gets to his sixth Test hundred! Back of a length, outside off. Labuschagne looks to block but it goes off the thick outside edge past the slip cordon and races away to the fence. What a gritty knock this has been from him! He punches the air in delight and gets a hug from his mate, Steven Smith!
Good-length delivery, around off. Marnus Labuschagne blocks it out to cover.

Oh, dear! That came from nowhere! This was a good-length ball, around off and taking off from a length. Marnus Labuschagne looks to block but he gets hit on the shoulder of his bat and he loses the grip on his bat as well.
On a length, angling down leg. Steven Smith misses his flick. Jos Buttler does well behind the sticks to move across to his left to gather the ball.
Another full ball, around off. Steven Smith hangs back and pushes it to mid on.
FOUR! Glorious! Fuller in length, outside off. Steven Smith moves across in his crease and caresses it through the cover region for a boundary.
Good-length delivery, outside off. Steven Smith lets it through to the keeper.
Back of a length, jagging back in from outside off. Steven Smith leaves it for the keeper to collect.
Short of a length, way outside off. Steven Smith shoulders arms to it.
Short of a length, around off. Marnus Labuschagne gets behind the line of the ball and blocks it.
Good-length delivery, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone.
BEATEN! Back of a length, outside off and curling away a bit. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend but the ball whistles past his outside edge.
Good-length ball, around off and shaping away late. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend but he misses and gets hit on his thigh pad.
Anderson bangs it into the deck, around middle and leg. Steven Smith stays back and pulls it along the ground towards deep square leg for one.
Fuller in length, outside off. Steven Smith stays back and drives it towards mid off.
On a length, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne shoulders arms to this one.
Leg bye! Back of a length, around leg. Steven Smith stays back and looks to flick but he misses. The ball ricochets off his thigh pad towards fine leg for a leg bye.
Good-length delivery, jagging back in late, around leg. Marnus Labuschagne looks to block but it goes off the thick inside edge towards fine leg for a run. Labuschagne moves to 96!
Much better from Broad! A length ball, angling in from outside off. Marnus Labuschagne defends it off the front foot.
This is a wayward ball, well outside off. Marnus Labuschagne offers no shot to this one.
Broad starts with a length ball, around off. Marnus Labuschagne hangs back in his crease to block this one out.
Stuart Broad (16-5-34-1) to bowl from the opposite end.
On a length, just outside off and angling in late. Steven Smith lets it be.
Back of a length, way outside off. Steven Smith leaves it alone.
FOUR! Steven Smith is up and running on Day 2! Anderson shortens his length, outside off. Smith stays back and cuts it past the point fielder for a boundary.
Also, the Australian players and the umpires will wear black arm bands today to pay respects for those involved in the Devenport tragedy on 16th Decemeber, 2021.
Lovely delivery! This was a good-length ball, around the fourth stump channel and curling away late. Smith looks to poke at it at first but sways away from the line in the end.
Back of a length, around off. Steven Smith moves across in his crease and blocks it out.
Anderson starts with a good-length delivery, outside off. Steven Smith lets it through to the keeper.
The first session is set to begin. The England players take the field. Followed by Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith who walk out to bat for Australia. James Anderson to start with the ball.

England got off to a start that they were hoping for on Day 1 as they got rid of Marcus Harris very early and their new ball bowlers in James Anderson and Stuart Broad executed their plans to perfection. However, the Aussie batters came hard at them in the second session and they were put under pressure. The short ball ploy worked to certain extent for the tourists as they got the crucial wicket of David Warner and it was Ben Stokes who struck for England at a crucial juncture. The visitors would be gutted with themselves as they could have easily got a couple of wickets more had they taken their catches and that would have completely changed the complexion of the first day of this intriguing Test. Joe Root and his men would hope that they make early inroads on Day 2 and not let the Aussies run away with the first innings score. Also, the new pink ball is just 9 overs old and the English bowlers should use it to their advantage in the first session. Will England bounce back in the first session? Will Marnus Labuschagne get to his 6th Test hundred? Lots of things to look forward to in the first session on Day 2.

Australia started steadily on Day 1 of the pink-ball Test after losing Marcus Harris early, but once Warner got his eye in, he took the attack to the opposition and runs started to flow for them. Marnus Labuschagne didn't look at his absolute best but he held one end and made sure that the loose deliveries were punished. He got a couple of lives from Jos Buttler as he was put down twice (On 21 and 95) and Labuschagne would hope that he converts this one into a big one and help his team to post a big total in the first innings. It was David Warner who was dismissed in the nervous 90's yet again but Steven Smith came in at number 4 and looked solid in the middle. The Aussies will now hope that they get as many runs as possible until the Tea break on Day 2, so that they can test the English batters under the lights in the last session.

Hello and a very warm welcome to Day 2 of the second Ashes Test between Australia and England. The first day of the pink-ball Test saw the hosts riding the advantage as they came back really well after the Dinner break after having kept on their toes in the first session by the English bowlers. England failed to capitalize on the start that they got and the fielders didn't help their bowlers either.
...Day 2, Session 1...

So! End of a day which began brightly for England ends on a sorry note. But there is some good news for English fans. One of their stars for the future, Tom-Kohler Cadmore, has smoked a stunning 92 in just 55 balls for the Jaffna Kings in the Lanka Premier League. Do switch tabs to cover all the action from that series but also remember to tune back in here when Day 2 of this Test resumes on Friday, 17th December, 2021. The first ball will be bowled at 2.30 pm local (0400 GMT) but as you are aware, the build up will begin well in advance. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

Marnus Labuschagne is in for a chat. He says, the last passage of play really tested them. Adds, Buttler dropping that catch (on 95) was unbelievable and he would look to capitalize on it on Day 2. Mentions, he feels for Warner, he played a patient knock but was unable to make his century. Ends by saying, his comments in the middle are mostly self-talk, but it may also add on to the pressure of the bowler. 2 birds with one stone he says with a smile.

England had their noses ahead after the first session as their bowlers stuck to their plans and executed them well. Broad and Anderson were impressive as ever at the start and the likes of David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne found it hard to negotiate the quality of English bowling. However, nothing went the visitors way in the next couple of sessions as they managed to get just one wicket post Dinner and it was Jos Buttler who dropped a couple of sitters behind the sticks which could prove to be very costly for them in the end. All the English bowlers bowled their hearts out and it was Ben Stokes who took the big wicket of David Warner and denied him his 25th Test hundred. All the bowlers bowled good probing lines and lengths but the Aussie batters had answers to all of them. To add insult to England's injury, they have also wasted a couple of reviews and are left with only 1 now. They got the new pink ball later in the day under the lights which did not do much but Anderson did create an opportunity which was dropped by Buttler yet again. What a contrasting second half of the day it has been for Jos Buttler! He took a stunner to dismiss Marcus Harris and then dropped a couple of dollies post Dinner session. The English bowlers will need to come back harder on Day 2 and get early breakthroughs and ensure that the hosts don't run away with the first innings score.

Having opted to bat first after winning the all-important toss, Australia were put on the back foot straightaway by the English bowlers as they lost their opener in Marcus Harris for just 3 runs. England's veteran, James Anderson and Stuart Broad set the tone early with the new ball as they kept things in check and did not give any opportunities to Aussie batters to free their arms. David Warner who is known to be an aggressive batter was forced to change his style of play as well. However, as the ball got older, both David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne started to play their shots and the Aussies certainly got a move on. Just when Warner was looking to up the ante, he perished for 95 and missed out on another well-deserved hundred. Steven Smith joined Marnus Labuschagne in the middle and he too looked in good nick. Both these batters managed to survive the most crucial phase of the day, when the artificial lights came on, thanks to that drop catch by Jos Buttler just minutes before stumps. All in all, it was a good day for the Aussies and they have justified their stand-in skipper's decision of batting first.

What an enthralling day of Test cricket we have witnessed at the ever-so scenic Adelaide Oval. The Aussies though would be the happier of the two sides as they have done well to pile up the runs after losing their opener early on in the day. The visitors would be a bit disappointed as they weren't able to capitalize on the start that they got with the ball.

Great discussions between Shane Warne and Michael Hussey on air. Warney's favourite topic has been over rates and England have been appalling again, in this Test, after losing points in the last game. So Warne just recounts the earlier rule - captain being suspended for the next match. Another suggestion he gives is awarding a certain amount of runs to the opposition for every over pending at the end of the day's play. He then asks for suggestions as to how can the over rate improve because he mentions that if there is a game where you would want as many overs as possible, it is the pink-ball Test, where you have just a small amount of time, perhaps just a session to make the ball talk. To this, Mr. Cricket has a kind view. He reminds Warney that with reviews in use these days, one review results in almost 5 minutes of no play. So that is one consideration to be taken. Then, he agrees that players need to be more responsible. For instance, Warne remembers an incident after Tea today where, Root was discussing the field with his bowler after entering the field. What were they doing during the break? And to this, Mussey adds that he saw Warner and Labuschagne change gloves a bit too often than required. So clearly, the issue is with both sides but be it Warne or Hussey or the ICC, we are still struggling in enforcing discipline in terms of over rates.

Great gesture by David Warner. We saw plenty of reactions on his dismissal. First of all, he was dismayed, having picked out the only fielder in that direction in the ring. A meter either side of Broad and it would have been a boundary. He just stood there, looking at Stokes, then Labuschagne and then the ground. He trudged off, shaking his head but then, while walking back towards the dressing room, he showed a thumbs up to the entire crowd. And then, the icing on the cake - just when he was about to enter the gates heading towards the dressing room, he threw his gloves to a couple of young kids in the ground. Boy, were they thrilled! Great to see this kind of an attitude from the senior statesman.

A good session for Australia despite some good bowling by English bowlers they have managed to play out the whole session without losing a wicket. Marnus Labuschagne looked iffy against the short ball and almost gave away a wicket at the start of the session but luckily for him the catch was dropped. David Warner at the other end played some adventurous shots and got to his fifty and eventually, Marnus Labuschagne also got more comfortable as they notched up a century partnership. Australia are in a commanding position now and will be looking to continue their good work in what is expected to be the toughest session to bat. Will England fight back or will Australia continue their march? We shall find that out. Do join us at 7.30 pm local (9.00 am GMT) for the final session of Day 1.

Yet another session where English bowlers tried hard but did not get the result they desired. England started with bowling good disciplined lines and lengths and a short ball ploy by Stokes nearly worked against Marnus Labuschagne but Jos Buttler behind the stumps failed to latch onto it. They kept bowling hard lengths and created few chances but failed to get the breakthrough as David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne piled on the runs. The post-Tea session is known to help bowlers a bit more in the pink-ball Test and England will hope that the coming session will bring more wickets for them.

Right then. Will the hosts be able to up the ante in the second session? Or will the England bowlers continue to cause trouble? Do join us in a short while to find out. Another exciting session awaits which will begin at 5.10 pm local (6.40 am GMT).

What a bowling show by the visitors! Unlike the first game, the bowlers aren’t being taken for aplenty. James Anderson and Stuart Broad’s inclusion has provided a lot of control with the ball for the visitors. It was Stuart Broad who drew the first blood in his 150th Test match. Later, Ollie Robinson and Chris Woakes joined the attack and probed good lines and lengths but did not find any success. Surely, the seamers made the batters earn the runs here. At the fag end of the session, Ben Stokes troubled Marnus Labuschagne with some short deliveries and would look to attack instanly in the second session. Even, Joe Root got the ball to turn and would not be happy with the exclusion of Jack Leach into the side.

Runs for Warner and Harris came at a slow pace. It was not the start the hosts had envisioned for themselves. The latter though got slipped out as he went to attack a delivery down leg and Buttler came out with a spectacular to catch to send him back. No one can have any complaints about that one. Although, Warner has had an impact in the first hour of the session, not with the blade but because of the threat he possess, England lost two reviews as they looked to take him out early, but that was not the case. Warner and Labuschagne fared really well and stitched a good partnership. The only aim was to remain unscathed till the Dinner break and they did that.

It has been a good session of Test cricket. We witnessed some good battles between the two sides. A slow start for the hosts on Day 1, but England have done well to not leak away many runs. They have conceded just 45 runs from 25 overs and also got the wicket of Marcus Harris.

Oh dear, Stuart Broad beats him again. Marnus Labuschagne needs to be a little careful now. Good-length ball, on the fourth stump line. Marnus Labuschagne comes across and looks to block it out and gets beaten yet again, as the ball zips past the outside edge. Stuart Broad did everything right here, but was unable to get the edge into play. Brilliant over by him.
Absolute beauty! Marnus Labuschagne gets beaten again. On a length, around off, nipping away. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend it out but the ball beats the outside edge.
BEATEN! A fuller-length delivery, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne prods and looks to drive it through cover. The ball goes through to the keeper.
Some movement this time! Good-length ball, outside off. The ball nips away off the seam. Marnus Labuschagne misses his attempt to defend and the ball goes past the outside edge.

NO BALL! Overpitched, around middle and leg. David Warner plays the on drive towards long on and the batters run three before the fielder cuts it out. The umpire signals a no ball, as the bowler oversteps.
Much better this time from Stuart Broad! A length ball, on off. David Warner presses forward and blocks it back to the bowler.
Stuart Broad serves a short ball, outside off. David Warner stays back and cuts it hard towards point. Haseeb Hameed is positioned well to collect the ball.
Stuart Broad (4-2-4-1) comes back to bowl. He replaces Chris Woakes.
Back of a length, on off. Marnus Labuschagne gets across and blocks it out. Another maiden for England. It has been a good battle.
Length and outside off, Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone for the keeper.
A sharp bouncer, wide of off stump. Marnus Labuschagne ducks under this one.
Length ball, around off, nipping in off the deck. Marnus Labuschagne inside-edges it onto the pads as he looks to defend it out off the front foot.
Back of a length, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone for the keeper.
Back of a length, on the pads, Marnus Labuschagne stays back and flicks it to square leg.
Another maiden for Chris Woakes. On a length, around off. Warner helps it towards cover-point.
Fuller and on off. David Warner drives it towards cover but straight to the fielder.
Back of a length, outside off, David Warner shoulders his arms to it.
Touch short, outside off, Warner cuts it to backward point but Hameed does well to stop it.
Full-length ball, around off. David Warner creams the drive towards cover. Dawid Malan gets low to his left and stops it brilliantly.
Fuller, on the pads, David Warner flicks it to mid-wicket but straight to the fielder.
Length and outside off. Marnus Labuschagne lets it go to the keeper. Another great over by Ollie Robinson and another maiden for him.
Fuller and outside off, Marnus Labuschagne drives it towards mid off.
Short and on off. Marnus Labuschagne remains solid in his defense.
Back of a length, on off. Marnus Labuschagne defends it solidly.

" placeholder="Please insert here...">14.2: Ollie Robinson to Marnus Labuschagne, Brilliant leave by Marnus Labuschagne in the end. Length ball, pitching outside off. Marnus Labuschagne was ready to play at it, but the ball nips in a long way. Marnus Labuschagne shoulders his arms and gets pinged above the pads. Missing the stumps clearly. No appeal and just "Ooohhs" and "Aahhss" from the slip cordon.
Good-length ball, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne shoulders his arms to it. He is not dealing with any ball outside off.
Outside off, left alone by Warner. 5 runs coming off the over.
WIDE! A sharp bumper, on leg. David Warner ducks under it. The umpire signals a wide due to the height.
Length and on top of off. David Warner defends it on the front foot.
FOUR! David Warner gets the first boundary of the game. Chris Woakes serves it short and outside off. David Warner rides the bounce and cuts it through covers for a boundary.
A length ball, around middle and leg, nipping in off the deck. David Warner looks to defend it out but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Back of a length, around off, shaping away from the left-hander. David Warner shoulders his arms.
Good length and on off. Warner stays back and defends it out solidly.
A length ball, around middle and off, on the stumps. Marnus Labuschagne defends it towards short mid on. A maiden over for Ollie Robinson now.
Good-length ball, around middle. Marnus Labuschagne squares up and defends it back towards the bowler, showing the full face of the bat.
Back of a length, on top of off. Marnus Labuschagne stays inside the crease and defends it watchfully.
Ollie Robinson serves a length delivery, on the fourth stump line. Marnus Labuschagne stays back and shoulders his arms to it.
A fuller length and on off. Marnus Labuschagne stands back and defends it to cover.
A length ball, on off. Marnus Labuschagne blocks it towards mid on.

DRINKS! The first hour of the day belongs to the visitors! The English bowlers have been right on the money with the pink ball and they have kept things really tight in the middle. Things don't look good for Australia as David Warner doesn't seem to be at his best and the rib injury looks to be bothering him.
Fuller and on off. David Warner hangs back and defends it onto the pitch. Another maiden for Chris Woakes.
Good-length ball, outside off. David Warner shoulders his arms.
Back of a length, outside off. Warner leaves it alone for the keeper.
Outside off, left alone by Warner.

Joe Root opts for a review yet again! The English players look confident! Was there any bat involved in it? The Hot Spot shows that there was a mark on the back pad and the TV umpire doesn't overturn the on-field decision.

NOT OUT! After several replays of the Hot Spot. The third umpire says, it was inconclusive, as they could not make a difference if it hit the pad or bat first. David Warner survives the review. A length ball, around leg, the ball straightens a bit. David Warner looks to defend it out but misses and gets hit on the pads. Chris Woakes appeals but the umpire is unmoved. The RTS shows that the pad is being hit, but it is inconclusive, as the bat is very close to the ball and the Hot Spot showed a small dot on the blade. Hence, the third umpire asks the umpire to stick to his original decision.
Touch short, around middle and leg. David Warner blocks it back to the keeper.
This one stays a little low. Touch fuller, around middle and leg. The ball stays low off the deck. Marnus Labuschagne gets some bat on it and digs it out.
Length and on off, Marnus Labuschagne blocks it out watchfully.
On a length, outside off. Lifts off the seam with some inward movement. Marnus Labuschagne moves back in time and leaves it for the keeper.
Good-length ball, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone for the keeper.

Two more! If it was a direct hit, Marnus Labuschagne could've been in trouble. Fuller and on the pads, Marnus Labuschagne flicks it to square leg. He calls for two, the fielder collects the ball and throws it at the keeper, who clips the bails. Marnus Labuschagne's dive saves him this time. The batters get two runs in the end.

A full-length ball, on the pads, Marnus Labuschagne clips it through mid-wicket. The batters take two comfortably. Marnus Labuschagne wanted the third run as well but Warner sent him back smartly, as the fielder was already on the ball.
Ollie Robinson comes into the attack now. He replaces James Anderson.
Woakes starts with a maiden over! A length ball, around off. David Warner defends it solidly towards cover.
Fuller in length, outside off. David Warner drags it to mid on.
Length ball, darted on the pads. David Warner misses his flick and gets hit high on his pads.
Good-length ball, outside off. David Warner lets it through to the keeper.
Back of a length, around the fourth stump channel. David Warner shoulders arms to this one.
Chris Woakes comes into the attack now. He replaces Stuart Broad.
Full ball, outside off. David Warner looks to drive but gets a thick inside edge to the leg side.
Length ball, around off. Marnus Labuschagne presses forward and defends it to cover.

Finally, David Warner is off the blocks! Full ball, around off. Warner pushes it back to the bowler who half-stops it and the ball goes towards mid off. Warner scampers through for a single and gets off the mark on his 20th delivery.
Fuller in length, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne prods and drives it past the mid off fielder. The batters take three runs.
A stifled appeal for LBW but the umpire is unmoved! This was a good-length ball, jagging back in from off. Marnus Labuschagne looks to leave it but the ball hits him high on his pad.
Fuller in length, way outside off. Marnus Labuschagne lets it through to the keeper.
Length ball, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone.

NOT OUT! David Warner escapes! Good-length delivery, around off and angling in sharply. Warner looks to block but he misses and gets hit high on his pad. Stuart Broad appeals and the umpire says no. England opt for a review but the Hawk Eye suggests that the impact is umpire's call and the wickets is missing. The on-field decision remains!

Joe Root takes a review for caught behind! The hot spot shows no bat is involved. RTS shows there is no spike as the ball passes the blade. The Ball Tracker shows the ball is missing the wickets. The original decision of not out stands. England lose a review here.
Marnus Labuschagne is up and running! Full ball, angling in from middle. Marnus Labuschagne drives it past the mid on fielder and the batters take three runs.
Back of a length, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone.
Marnus Labuschagne comes in at number 3.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! What a catch from Jos Buttler behind the sticks! England get their breakthrough and they are delighted! Broad bangs it into the deck, around leg. Marcus Harris stays back and looks to hook it behind square on the leg side but he gets a feather and Jos Buttler behind the sticks dives full stretch to his right and takes a stunner! This is a much-deserved wicket for Stuart Broad and the English bowlers finally get their reward!
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, nipping back in from off. Marcus Harris defends it to mid on.
Length ball, on off. Marcus Harris blocks it out.
BEATEN! Top delivery from the veteran! David Warner is yet to get off the mark! Good-length ball, around off and shaping away late. Warner looks to defend but the ball beats his outside edge.
Length ball, angling in from middle. David Warner defends it watchfully.
Length ball, around off. David Warner looks to defend but the ball takes the outside edge and goes to the backward point region.
Back of a length, around off. David Warner covers the line of the delivery and blocks it.
Short of a length, on off. David Warner sits back and pushes it to cover.
On a length, around middle. David Warner defends it out.
Good-length ball, around leg. Marcus Harris tucks it to square leg.
NO BALL! Good-length ball, on off. Marcus Harris blocks it out. No ball called as Stuart Broad oversteps.
After seeing the review. Marnus Labuschagne is elated by the decision. He is seen punching the helmet in the pavilion.
Length ball, around off. Marcus Harris looks for a booming drive but it goes off the inside half of the bat towards mid on.
Full ball, down leg. Marcus Harris misses his flick.
Full ball, outside off. Marcus Harris looks to drive but it goes off the inner half of the blade to mid-wicket.

Review taken by Marcus Harris for LBW. The original decision is out. The hot spot shows no bat is involved and same with the RTS. The Ball Tracker shows the ball is missing the wickets by a long way, going over the stumps. Marcus Harris survives. The review has worked in their favour and Harris lives another day.

NOT OUT! Marcus Harris survives! That is a good review from Harris! This was a full ball, around off and jagging back in sharply. Harris looks to block but he misses and gets rapped in front. Broad appeals and the umpire raises his finger. Harris opts for a review and the Hawk Eye suggests that the ball would have gone down leg so the on-field decision is overturned!
Fuller in length, way outside off. Marcus Harris shoulders arms to this one.
Good-length delivery, outside off and shaping away late. David Warner leaves it alone watchfully.
On a length, around off. David Warner gets behind the line of the ball and defends it to cover.
Back of a length, outside off. David Warner shoulders arms to this one.
That is a peach of a delivery! Good-length ball, around off and curling away late. Warner stays back and looks to defend but the ball zips past his outside edge.
Short of a length, outside off and shaping away. David Warner lets it through to the keeper.
Good-length ball, around the fourth stump and moving away late. David Warner leaves it alone.
Broad goes fuller this time, around off. Marcus Harris plays an on drive but finds James Anderson at mid on.
Back of a length, way outside off. Marcus Harris sways away from the line of the delivery.

Stuart Broad got the better of David Warner 7 times out of 10 during the 2019 Ashes Test series. David Warner could only rack up 35 runs against the seamer. The most awaited battle is back on now and Broad has been all over Warner. He has already struck him a couple of times on the pads at the start of the day.
Fuller in length, way outside off. Marcus Harris does not offer any shot to this one.
A loud shout for LBW but the umpire says no! Good-length ball, around off and jagging back in late. Marcus Harris looks to block but gets an inside edge onto his pad.
Good-length ball, around leg. Marcus Harris looks to flick but misses and gets hit on his thigh pad.
Back of a length, nipping back in sharply from off. Marcus Harris looks to leave it but the ball jags back and hits him high on his pad.
First runs on the board for Marcus Harris and Australia! Anderson hurls a full ball, on the pads. Harris flicks it past the mid on fielder and the batters take three runs.
Back of a length, around off. Marcus Harris gets behind the line of the delivery and blocks it out.
Shorter in length, outside off. Marcus Harris lets it be.
Short of a length, outside off. Marcus Harris lets it through to the keeper.
A bit fuller this time, outside off. Marcus Harris shoulders arms to it.
BEATEN! Good-length delivery, around off and shaping away late. Marcus Harris looks to defend but the ball zips past his outside edge.
Back-to-back maiden overs! This is a good-length ball, way outside off. David Warner sways away from the line of the ball. Australia yet to get off the mark.
Fuller in length, outside off. David Warner prods and drives it to cover. Cannot find the gap though. Warner was quick to pass on the message to Harris by a loud "NO".
Length ball, nipping back in from off. Warner blocks it back to the bowler.
Full ball, around off. David Warner pushes it back to the bowler.
Length ball, down leg. David Warner misses his flick and Jos Buttler moves to his right behind the sticks to gather the ball.

A huge appeal for LBW but the umpire is not interested! Broad comes 'round the wicket straightaway and hurls a length ball, around middle which angles in late. David Warner sits back and shoulders arms to this one. He gets hit high on his pad. Top start from Stuart Broad.
Stuart Broad to bowl from the other end.
A maiden over to start the proceedings in this pink-ball Test! Length ball, way outside off. Marcus Harris does not offer any shot to this one.
Good-length delivery, ouside off and going on with the angle. Marcus Harris shoulders arms to this one.
A bit fuller this time, around off. Marcus Harris defends it to cover.
Back of a length, on middle. Marcus Harris blocks it out.
BEAUTY! Movement early on for James Anderson! Length ball, around off and curling away late. Marcus Harris has a tentative poke at it but the ball goes past his outside edge.
Anderson starts with a good-length ball, outside off. Marcus Harris leaves it alone.

The game is set to begin. The England players stride out and take the field. Followed by David Warner and Marcus Harris who walk out to open for Australia. James Anderson to steam in with the new ball. Here we go...

Joe Root, the captain of England, is in for a chat. He says, they would’ve batted first as well. Adds, it looks like a good surface. Mentions, Stuart Broad comes in and marks his 150th Test match, while Jack Leach has been left out. Ends by saying, it is a brave call and hope the seamers can make use of the conditions.

Steven Smith, the stand-in skipper of Australia, says that they will bat first. Adds that it is a huge honour for him to lead his country. Tells that it looks like a typical Adelaide day-night pitch which has plenty of grass on it. Mentions that Cummins and Hazlewood are big losses for them but they are excited to see what Jhye Richardson and Michael Neser can do.

England (Playing XI) - Rory Burns, Haseeb Hameed, Dawid Malan, Joe Root (C), Ben Stokes, Ollie Pope, Jos Buttler (WK), Chris Woakes, Ollie Robinson, James Anderson (In place of Mark Wood), Stuart Broad (In place of Jack Leach).

Australia (Playing XI) - David Warner, Marcus Harris, Marnus Labuschagne, Steven Smith (C), Travis Head, Cameron Green, Alex Carey (WK), Michael Neser (In place of Pat Cummins), Mitchell Starc, Nathan Lyon, Jhye Richardson (In place of Josh Hazlewood).
TOSS - The coin goes up and lands in favour of Australia. They have elected to BAT first.
UPDATE - Stuart Broad is being presented his 150th Test cap from the veteran James Anderson. So both Broad and Anderson will be playing this pink-ball Test match.

UPDATE - Big news coming in from Adelaide is that Pat Cummins has been ruled out of the second Test as he has come in close contact with a Covid case. Michael Neser is set to replace him and it will be Steven Smith who will be leading the side in Cummins' absence. Michael Neser is set to make his debut and receives the baggy green from Glenn McGrath.

England struggled to put on an exhibition with the bat in both the innings. They were forced to reshuffle their squad coming into this game, and why wouldn’t they? This time they have made sure to involve James Anderson in their 12-man squad. Four years ago, Anderson played a day-night game at Adelaide and racked up a five-wicket haul. The visitors would hope the pacer can replicate this and make the ball dance on his tunes. Their batters need to make sure to stick around in the middle and focus on stitching partnerships, unlike the first game. Yet again, Jonny Bairstow has been excluded from the 12-man squad. How costly will it prove to be for the visitors? Also, will they exclude Stuart Broad in the second Test match as well? We shall wait and find out. Stay tuned for toss and more updates.

Are you really telling me Pat Cummins is captaining the side for the first time ever? He looked a natural in that role. Along with a flying start to the captaincy, Pat Cummins ran riot with the ball in the first innings and crowned his captaincy with a five-wicket haul. The visitors were bundled out for 147. It was then a master-class by Travis Head, which took the game away from England. After coming of off a nine-wicket victory over the visitors, Australia cannot afford to sit back, because this time it will be a swing-friendly affair in a day-night Test in Adelaide. Also, the hosts will be missing the services of Josh Hazlewood and Jhye Richardson will come into the side as his replacement, he has a good record in a day-night Test. Australia will be looking forward to extend their unbeaten run in the pink-ball Test match.

Hello and a warm welcome to all! It is time for the second Ashes Test match between Australia and England. The Ashes 2021-22, started off with a bang, it was a dominating performance by the hosts, and they have taken a 1-nil lead in this series. This game will be a pink-ball Test match. England will need a rub of the green to level the series. As history suggests, England have never won an Ashes series in Australia after losing the first Test match since 1954-55.
... Day 1, Session 1 ...

We are back for Australia's second innings! Joe Root has his team in a huddle and has a few words before leading them out on the field. Marcus Harris and David Warner are out in the middle. Warner is taking the strike and James Anderson is set to steam in.

Australia have a massive lead now! What a turnaround we have witnessed. England won the first session but after that, things went downhill. After losing Burns and Hameed cheaply, Malan and Root steadied the ship and England fought hard and came right back in this contest. However, both Malan and Root were denied their hundreds and the tourists were left in a spot of bother. It was Ben Stokes who showed great resistance against the Aussie bowlers but he ran out of partners and had to change his gears eventually. He too fell after smacking a couple of lusty blows and England were bundled out for 236. Australian bowlers came back really well in the second session and got rid of both the set batters in Malan and Root. It was Cameron Green who got the priced wicket of Root. Mitchell Starc also got into the act as he chipped in with a couple of wickets. However, it was Nathan Lyon who did the damage in the third session and he sent back a couple of English batters. It has been a terrific comeback from the hosts with the ball and they are well ahead in this game now. Also, Australia haven't enforced the follow-on and they will bat again.

OUT! CAUGHT! England are bowled out for 236. Stuart Broad looks to go downtown but miscues his hit. Mitchell Starc gets his fourth wicket of the game. Touch short, around middle and leg. Broad moves back and looks to heave it away. The ball flies towards cover off the outer half. Head settles under it and takes it easily. 50 wickets in Day-Night Tests for Mitchell Starc. ENGLAND TRAIL BY 237 RUNS.
Commentary.Howout: c Travis Head b Mitchell Starc

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Nicely played! Full length and on off. James Anderson shuffles across and clips it through square leg to bag a boundary.
Length ball, angled into the batter again. James Anderson looks to defend it out but misses to get hit just under the box. He would be glad.
A length ball, angled into the batter. James Anderson looks to defend it out but gets banged on the pads.
Short and on off. Stuart Broad pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
Banged in a short ball, on off. Broad leaves it alone.

SIX! BANG! Mitchell Starc holds the catch on the ropes. He has a big smile on his face. Stuart Broad gets lucky and gets his 50th Test match six of his career. Back of a length ball, around middle and leg. Stuart Broad looks to hook it away. The ball takes the outside edge and flies towards fine leg. Mitchell Starc grabs the ball safely only to realise he has stepped on the ropes, as he tumbles on the ground.
OH, Well bowled. Got too much curve on it this time. Fuller, around off, shaping away. James Anderson looks to dig it out but gets beaten by the shape.
Slightly short, on middle and off. Anderson shuffles across and defends it solidly.
Fuller, on the pads, Stuart Broad clips it to deep mid-wicket for a single.

Ahem, ahem - When Broady comes to Australia, sledging is turned full on! After the end of the previous over, David Warner went across and had a dig at both Broad and Anderson. It did not look serious but umpire Rod Tucker had to ask Warner to go back to his fielding position! You do not want to make either of these two fast bowlers grumpy, do you? This is just the first inning of the second Test of a 5-match series. You still have got to bat against these blokes!
Short ball, around middle and leg. Broad leans back and leaves it alone.
Short ball, around off. Stuart Broad stays back and looks to heave it away but misses.
Sharp bumper, arouund middle and leg. Stuart Broad sways away from the line of the delivery.
Back of a length, around leg. Stuart Broad hangs back and clips it past short leg for a single.

TWO LEG BYES! Short ball, on the body. Broad jumps and leans back in the process. The ball goes off the arm over Alex Carey to fine leg. The batters collect a couple of runs, as the fielder takes some time to get to the ball.
Back of a length, around middle, shaping away. Stuart Broad leaves it alone.
Another short delivery, on the bodyline. Stuart Broad blocks it to short leg.
Back of a length, on the bodyline. Stuart Broad hops inside the crease and defends it out to the leg side.

A slight halt in play. The physio is out in the middle after that blow to Broad's helmet. As per the concussion rules, Broad needs to change his helmet. In a way, it is good that the ball hit the gloves first. Else that jaw would have taken a pounding, if the ball had hit it directly. Broad certainly looks rattled. On comes the new helmet.
NASTY!! That must've hurt. Short ball, on the bodyline. Stuart Broad hops and looks to defend it out. The ball goes of his gloves and hits the grill on its way.
Jhye Richardson (17-4-66-0) is back on too.
A maiden for Mitchell Starc. Length and on off. James Anderson blocks it out watchfully.
Good-length ball, outside off. James Anderson looks to have a poke at it but pulls his blade back eventually. The ball zips past the outside edge.
Short and on off. The ball flies off the deck. James Anderson hangs back and defends it out solidly.

Good to see Warner back on the field. By the way, Shane Warne is thinking aloud whether Smith will enforce the follow-on if he gets the chance. Yes, the lead is well above 200 but look at the overs bowled. That is almost a full day's play and Australia will think about resting their bowlers. However, Warney also remembers the previous time these two teams met at the Adelaide Oval - Australia were shot out for 138 in the third innings, with Jimmy rocking them hard. Yes, Australia still won that game but it does seem that batting third in Australia is the most difficult thing to do. Remember Adelaide 2020, where India were shot out for 36? So Shane reckons that Smith would be desperate to take the last wicket as quickly as possible, enforce the follow-on and take another 3-4 by Stumps tonight. Oh and Warne adds that there is RAIN FORECAST for tomorrow. Ah....
BEATEN! Shapes away nicely. Good-length ball, around off. The ball nips away off the deck. James Anderson looks to defend it out but gets beaten at the outside edge.
Back of a length, on off, close to the body. James Anderson hops and defends it out.
Massive bounce and swing! Back of a length, way outside off, shaping away. James Anderson looks to chase it but misses.
The new ball is available now and it is not a surprise that it is taken! Mitchell Starc (14-5-36-3) is on now.
Length ball, around off. Broad looks to block but gets the toe end towards first slip.
Short of a length, around off. Pushed to point for one.

Robbed of a 'Stokes'ingley! If this had been the earlier Stuart Broad, we would have seen normal cricket, with Stokes rotating the strike and Broad playing watchful cricket. However, after Broad was hit on the nose by a Varun Aaron bouncer in 2014, he has never been the same batter. Hence, Stokes was forced to take matters into his own hands.
Short of a length, outside off. Anderson looks to block but is beaten.
James Anderson comes out to bat now. Anderson and Broad together! This time with the bat. Can they make Australia bat again with a nice little partnership?

OUT! BOWLED! Green does the trick! Stokes really had no other option but to attack now! Green bowls it short of a length and outside off. Stokes looks to slog it away but gets the inside edge. The ball goes back to hit the stumps and England's chances of avoiding the follow on are dismal now.
Commentary.Howout: b Cameron Green

Commentary.Commentary: Stokes looks to go downtown but gets it towards deep square leg.

Short and outside off. Stokes slams it to the left of deep point. Harris gets across and dives to stop it. His knee gets stuck in the ground and he has an awkward. Stokes has a surprised look after seeing that.
Stokes flicks it towards mid-wicket and takes a single.
FOUR! Up and over! Tossed up, outside off. Stokes backs away and goes heaves it over mid off for a boundary.

Uzzie lad is on the field! Yes, Usman Khawaja is on the field, as a substitute for David Warner. Ideally, Khawaja should have been playing in place of Marcus Harris but an injury ruled him out of the opening Ashes Test and then, he was picked to represent Australia A against England Lions in a 4-day game. As things stand, one certainly feels that UK will play against the team from the UK on Boxing Day but what about Mitchell Marsh? He has been in rollicking form, but don't think Travis Head or Cameron Green have done much wrong to be left out of the playing XI! A good selection headache for the think tank.
Shorter ball, around off. Pushed to covers.
SIX! All the way! We could be in for a T20-style game now! Tossed up, on off. Stokes gets low and slog-sweeps it over the mid-wicket fence.
Loopy ball, around off. Stokes gets the outside edge but it drops short of second slip.
Short and outside off. Cut away to deep cover. Single is not taken.
Short ball, outside off. Stokes ramps it to third man for one.
Short and on off. Stokes lets it go.
Short of a length, outside off. Stokes cuts it to covers.
Driven to long off but a single is not taken.
FOUR! Lucky boundary! Like we said, Stokes could cut loose now! Length ball, on off. Stokes looks to heave it away but gets the inside edge. It runs to the fine leg fence.
Short of a length, on off. Flicked to mid-wicket..
Turn and bounce! Tossed up, on a length, outside off. Stuart Broad looks to defend but the ball goes past his outside edge.
Flatter ball, on off. Stuart Broad blocks it out.
Who will walk out now? It is Stuart Broad.

Review! Ollie Robinson takes it upstairs for an LBW review. The orginal decision is OUT. The Hot Spot shows there is nothing on the blade. The RTS shows bat is absent. Impact is umpire's call and wickets are hitting. England do not lose a review here.

OUT! LBW! Nathan Lyon gets his third wicket and England are in deep trouble now! Flatter ball, outside off and spinning in sharply. How will Stokes play? The pitch is starting to play a few more tricks and he is running out of partners. The southpaw has looked quite solid so far and he has nothing to lose to be honest. We could see him take the bowlers on soon. What is the worst that could happen? He could get out. But if it pays out, England could get 40-50 runs in short time.

Ollie Robinson comes in at number 9. Will Australia straightaway take the second new ball once available? If we had been asked this a few minutes ago, it would have been a definite YES. However, now, things have changed. Nathan Lyon is settling into a real rhythm and at this point of time, one feels that that a wicket is around the corner, every 5 minutes. Once Garry gets into his zone, tailenders can get wiped out quickly.

A minute focus on keeping skills. If you look at Alex Carey, one needs to just watch when he actually gets up to collect the ball against Nathan Lyon. He is on his haunches right from the time Lyon starts his run up. Stays down, down, down, even when the ball is flighted. Then, he gets up after the ball lands on the deck. That way, he can exactly judge how the ball will spin or move and gather accordingly. If you are not a full-time wicketkeeper, you tend to get up a bit too early and in that process, either fumble or miss the ball.

The hosts are clearly on top now! It was Mitchell Starc who led the attack with the ball and bagged two wickets in this session. But it all started when Green sent back Root to the pavilion. The Australian bowlers managed to put a lid on the run rate, as the combination of Green and Lyon bowled 38 dot balls on the trot. Later, Lyon got himself into the wicket's column by getting rid of Ollie Pope. The gameplan for the hosts would be to bowl out England as soon as possible and get England to bat again under floodlights. Do join us at 7.30 pm local time (9 am GMT) for the final session of Day 3.

It was Déjà vu for the English camp. The pair of Root and Malan fared really well in the first session and started the second session positively, both the players knocked a boundary. But once Root slipped out, the floodgates opened up and wickets came at regular intervals to haunt the visitors. Stokes and Woakes managed to remain unscathed till the Tea break. Woakes played a couple of good shots, while Stokes focused on his defensive structure. Wonder what their approach will be with twilight and the new ball approaching.

What a great session of cricket, it was marked by a solid comeback from the Aussies. They have picked up 4 wickets in this session and only leaked 57 runs in 30 overs. England struggled to get back on their feet after losing the pair of Malan and Root.

It is very difficult to bowl well with both, the old and new ball. As a fast bowler. It is perhaps not that difficult to bowl well with the new ball, because you don't need to do much. But when the ball gets old, nothing much happens and that is when your credibility comes into account, as Jhye Richardson is finding out now. The great Waqar Younis had once said that when he played under Imran Khan, Imran never gave him the new ball as he did not want the youngster to compromise on his speed. When you are bowling with the old ball, you need to work really hard to make it move and get wickets and once you master that, the new ball becomes like a toy in your hands. Something which Richardson needs to learn.

But what we do not know from that scorecard is - after the wicket of Root, the combination of Lyon and Green bowled 38 DOT BALLS ON THE TROT. So clearly, the pressure was building and what seemed like a loose ball from Starc, turned out to be a wicket-taking one, that too, of a set batsman.

Mitchell Starc (7-3-24-1) comes into the attack. Surprising from Smith. One would have expected Green to continue, especially after his wicket of Root. He has been bowling well in this spell, giving just 6 runs in 5 overs. Perhaps, Smith does not want to overwork his allrounder and risk an injury. It is another hot day. Plus, it does seem like there is some reverse swing on offer. So who knows - throw the ball to Mitch and the next thing you know - bang, bang.

Phenomenal. That is the word to describe the GOAT. In the 43rd over, we saw a delivery. Short and slightly outside off. And after that, Lyon has bowled that type of a delivery to Malan, exactly identical. Once in the 47th over and the 49th over. In that first delivery, Malan got the cut shot away for a boundary through point. But after that, in spite of the length being the same, Dawid has struggled to put bat on ball. That is because of the extra bounce. So how come Lyon bowls the same ball but generates different types of bounce? The release. On the remaining occasions, Lyon delayed his release just a little bit, giving a little bit of flight, but not altering the length. So the batsman thinks that it is a short ball and runs are on offer, but is unable to pick the change in flight and pace.
