...Day 3, Session 2...

The Australian bowlers gave it their all in the first session but they failed to break the partnership between Joe Root and Dawid Malan. Steven Smith tried everything but the English pair had answers to all. Jhye Richardson looked threatening in his second spell where he bowled some top quality deliveries but luck didn't go his way. The pitch seems to have eased a little bit but there is certainly some turn in this track for Nathan Lyon. The Aussies would now look to come back strong in the second session and make early inroads. Will they be able to break this partnership and open the flood gates? Or will the English pair of Joe Root and Dawid Malan carry on with their resistance? We'll find that in the second session of the day which begins at 5.10 pm local time (6.40 am GMT).

This is exactly the kind of session that the English fans and the camp would have hoped for! The tourists have scored 123 runs in the first session without losing any wicket. Coming into Day 3, all the onus was on Malan and Root to bat through the opening session and set the tone for the rest of the Test and boy, have they delivered! Both Root and Malan had their share of luck but they also made sure that all the loose deliveries were punished. They have stitched together another important partnership and the English camp would hope that they dug in deep and bat long. Both Root and Malan have brought up their fifties and look all set to get a big one here.

What a session this has been for England! They have not only managed to survive but they have also scored at a good rate. The Aussies would be disappointed as they have failed to get an early breakthrough on Day 3 and have not been able to capitalize on the impressive start that was provided by their pacers under the lights on Day 2.
Back of a length, on off. Malan blocks it out solidly. THAT WILL BE DINNER ON DAY 3.
Length and on the pads, Malan blocks it out watchfully.

LEG BYE! A full-length ball, around off. The ball stays low and nips in off the surface. Root hangs back and looks to flick it away but misses to get pinged on the pads. The batters collect a leg bye. Cameron Green appeals for lbw but the umpire is unmoved.
On a length, on off. Root defends it to point.
Length, on fourth stump. Root defends it out.
Good length, on off. Root stays back and defends it towards point.
On a length, outside off, angled in. Malan covers his stumps and leaves it alone for the keeper.
Slightly short and on middle, Root swivels and pulls it to deep square leg. He rotates the strike.
Good length and outside off, Root shuffles across and leaves it alone.
Full and on off. Root leans in and drives it through the diving fielder at cover. The batters take two runs comfortably.
Another single now! Touch short and outside off. Malan pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Back of a length, around off. Root hops and guides it towards backward point for a run.
Fuller, on the pads, Root clips it to fine leg and gets off the mark with a single,
BEATEN! On a length, outside off, the ball straightens a bit after landing. Root presses forward, as he looks to defend it out but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Fuller and on off. Root stays inside the crease and blocks it out.
Good length, on top of off. Root defends it out.

FOUR! Runs are coming in thick and fast for England now! A full-length ball, angled down leg. Root stays back and glances it towards fine leg for a boundary. This also brings up Root's 52nd Test fifty. His team needed such an innings from him. But the job is still half done and Root would look to convert this into three digits.
Full length and on off. Root stays back and defends it out watchfully.
Touch short and outside off. Root punches it through point off the back foot for a single. 6 runs off it.
Fuller, on the pads, Malan clips it through mid-wicket and rotates the strike.
FOUR! Cracked! Back of a length, outside off. Malan stands tall and pulls it through mid-wicket for a boundary.

Hits the pad this time! A length ball, around off, nips away a bit. Malan puts his front leg forward and shoulders his arms. The ball rolls of the pads and goes behind. A stifled appeal but the umpire is not interested.
Outside off, on a length, nipping in. Malan covers his stumps and shoulders his arms.
Good length and outside off, nips in late. Malan shoulders his arms at it.
Cameron Green comes into the attack now.
Fuller, on middle and leg. Root clips it to square leg but finds the fielder.
OH BEAUTY! Good-length ball, around off. The ball nips in off the deck with some extra bounce. Root confidently shoulders his arms and trusts the bounce.
FOUR! Nicely played. Short ball, on the bodyline. Root swivels on the back foot and pulls it through square leg to bag a boundary.
A single now! On a length, around middle and leg. Dawid Malan flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.
Length and around off. Malan defends it to the off side without any hesitation.
Fuller and on the pads, Root hangs back and clips it to deep square leg for a single.
Fuller, on off. Malan drives it to cover but not in the gap though. First maiden for Nathan Lyon in 9 overs.
Flatter, angled onto the pads. Malan stays back and defends it to the leg side.
Looped up, full and on off. Malan blocks it out.
Tossed up, full and on off. Malan prods and defends it out.
Swing and a miss! So close! Flatter and short, outside off. Malan goes on the back foot and looks to cut it away but the ball sneaks past his outside edge.
Full and on off. Malan presses forward and defends it on the bounce to silly point.
Full length and on off. Root leans in and drives it to cover. Not in the gap though.
Length and on the pads, Malan flicks it to mid-wicket and crosses for a single.
Jhye Richardson comes 'round the wicket for the left-hander. On a length, on the fourth stump line. Malan hangs back and looks to defend it out but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Full length and outside off. Root steps forward and drives it past mid off. Head chases and does well to keep it down to a single.
Length and on off. Malan pushes it to cover and scampers through for a quick single.
LEG BYE! Back of a length ball, on the pads, Root stays back and looks to flick it away but misses. He gets hit just below the thigh pad and collects a leg bye as the ball rolls out.
Play and a miss! Flatter and quicker, outside off. Dawid Malan hangs back to cut but he misses as the ball spins past his outside edge.
Flatter ball, around off. Dawid Malan blocks it out.
Flatter ball, on a length, turning in late. Root waits for the ball to turn and turns it to wide of mid-wicket for a run.
Flatter ball, on middle. Dawid Malan nudges it to the leg side and collects a single. That brings up the 100-run stand between Malan and Root!
Nicely tossed up, on a length, around off and turning away late. Dawid Malan prods to block but leaves it alone in the end.
Flatter ball, turning down leg. Joe Root tucks it to the leg side for a run.

Conundrum. Especially if you are a wicketkeeper. Should I stand up or stay back? We have now spent a bit more than 2 days on this pitch. And though we cannot definitely say that the pitch has variable bounce, we have seen variable carry. Let's dissect. If the bowler pitches it full, getting the batsman forward to play, the edges are not carrying behind. But if the bowler bangs it short or around good length, the edge carries to above waist height. One can remember how Rory Burns got out last evening. So the question is - where does the keeper stand?
Back of a length, around off. Dawid Malan blocks it to cover.
Fuller in length, outside off. Joe Root drives it past the cover fielder but manages only a single as he did not time it that well. The stand moves to 98.
BEATEN! Good-length delivery, jagging back in sharply. Root prods to defend but the ball straightens a bit after pitching and goes past his outside edge.
Good-length ball, around off. Joe Root gets solid in his defense.
BEAUTY! Length ball, oustide off and angling in late. Root leaves it alone and the ball goes just past his off pole.
Back of a length, just outside off. Joe Root hangs back, rides the bounce well and taps it with soft hands to the gully region.
Jhye Richardson (9-3-29-0) is back into the attack now.
A bt quicker, on a length, around off. Dawid Malan stays back and looks to cut but it goes off the shoulder of his bat to backward point.
On a length, around off. Dawid Malan keeps it out watchfully.
Flatter ball, on off. Dawid Malan defends it off the front foot.
FOUR! CARESSED! Tossed up, on a length, outside off and spinning away late. Dawid Malan prods and carves it past the cover fielder to collect a boundary.
Flatter and quicker, on a length, around off. Dawid Malan presses forward and defends it solidly.
Flatter ball, on off. Dawid Malan blocks it out.
Fuller in length, on middle and leg. Joe Root presses forward and works it to mid on.
Length ball, around off. Joe Root presents the full face of the bat and pushes it straight back to hit the stumps at the non-striker's end.
On a length, around off. Joe Root defends it out.
FOUR! Top shot! Back of a length, outside off. Joe Root stays back, rides the bounce nicely and punches it past the cover fielder to bag a boundary.

Nicely played! Full ball, on middle and leg. Dawid Malan drives it past Mitchell Starc at mid on who dives to stop the ball but the ball goes past him and the batters collect three runs. 100 comes up for England.
Back of a length, outside off. Dawid Malan punches it to cover.
A stifled appeal from behind the sticks but the umpire is not interested! Flatter ball, fuller in length, around leg. Joe Root looks to sweep but he misses and gets hit low on his pad.

BREAKING NEWS - Ahh well, this is not going to sit well with English fans. The ICC has released a press statement that England have been DOCKED 8 POINTS for their slow overrate at the 'Gabba, instead of the previously mentioned 5. The clarification states that while the match fee is 20 percent per player for every delayed over, it cannot be more than 100 percent. But there is no cap on the deduction of points and hence, the actual number must be deducted. Well, after spending more than 150 overs and nearly 6 hours in the field, not what the news you wanted to wake up to.
Flatter ball, way outside off. Joe Root stays back and does not offer any shot to this one.
Another ball, shorter in length, around middle. Joe Root eases it to mid-wicket.
Flatter ball, shorter in length, outside off and turning in late. Joe Root tucks it to the leg side.
Loopy ball, on middle. Joe Root turns it past the short leg fielder.
Tossed up, outside off. Dawid Malan defends it to the point region and takes off for a run.
Length ball, jagging back in slightly from outside off. Joe Root prods to block this one out.
Good-length ball, outside off. Joe Root defends it solildy.
Back of a length, on off. Joe Root stays back and blocks it out.

Steven Smith opts to take the review for LBW at the final second! The original decision is not out. The replays show the ball is hitting the pad clearly. The Ball Tracker shows it is umpire's call on impact and the ball is missing the wickets by a long margin. Australia lose a review this time.

NOT OUT! Joe Root survives and Australia lose a review! This is a length ball, angling in from outside off. Root looks to defend off the front foot but he misses and gets rapped in front. Michael Neser appeals and the umpire says no. Steven Smith opts for a review but the Hawk Eye suggests that the ball would have gone well over the sticks so the on-field decision remains.
Short of a length, around leg. Dawid Malan pulls it to fine leg and collects a single. Fifty for Malan and this is his ninth in Test cricket! Not the most convincing though but he'll take that!
Back of a length, around off. Dawid Malan hangs back, opens the face of his bat and guides it to the slip fielder, on the bounce.
Nicely pushed off the front foot past covers for one.
Lyon drags his length back a bit and bowls this outside off. Malan stays in the crease to block it but the ball turns away and goes past the outside edge.
Root is sweeping nicely now. This goes to deep square leg for one. We can see more batters play this shot against Lyon.
Flatter ball, around off. Malan gets the thick inside edge towards square leg for a single.

Learning from our mistakes. We all should be doing that. But right now, Joe Root has done exactly that. A few minutes ago, Mark Waugh opined on air that perhaps the sweep shot is not the greatest option against Nathan Lyon on this pitch, as there is a bit of bounce here. Root tried that shot, got a top edge, survived but since then, has kept that shot in his bag. The genius has understood quickly enough what type of shots are NOT to be played against Lyon and that is the sign of a great player. Oops, just as we said that, there came another sweep! Careful, Joe!
Nice and full again, around off. Malan gets forward to block it well.
Lyon tosses it nicely, around off. Root gets low and sweeps it nicely to deep backward square leg for one.
Full ball, on middle. Dawid Malan drives it back past the bowler and collects a couple of runs.

Just short of the slip fielder! Good-length delivery, around off and curling away late. Malan looks to poke at it but he gets a thick outside edge which lands just in front of Steven Smith at third slip.
Length ball, angling in from off. Malan looks to defend by staying back in the crease but he gets an inside edge onto his pads. Luckily for Malan, the ball does not pop out back to the bowler.

Neser follows it up with a length ball, outside off and angling across the left-hander. Malan stays back and leaves it alone.
Banged into the deck, down leg. Dawid Malan ducks underneath!

FOUR! Root brings out the reverse sweep now! Loopy ball, on a length, outside off. Joe Root gets low and reverse sweeps it past the backward point fielder. Travis Head gives it a chase but the ball wins.
Flatter ball, outside off and turning in late. Joe Root gets back in his crease and then pushes it behind square on the off side.
Nicely tossed up, around middle. Joe Root prods and works it to mid-wicket.
A bit quicker, on a length, outside off. Joe Root blocks it to the point region.
Another ball, shorter in length, outside off and spinning in sharply. Root stays back and punches it to the point fielder.
Flatter ball, on off, turning in late. Joe Root blocks it out.

DRINKS! The tourists have negotiated the first hour of the day extremely well! Two of the most dependable batters of England have managed to not only survive but they have also scored at a brisk rate. Australia would look to break this partnership as early as possible and then chip in with wickets.

Full and on leg. Root clips it to mid-wicket for a single.

The first session is set to begin. The Australian players stride out to the middle. Followed by Joe Root and Dawid Malan who walk out to bat for England. Michael Neser will have the ball in hand to complete his over.

England find themselves in a tough position yet again in the Test series. Their bowlers were made to toil hard on Day 2 as well. It was Robinson who started the proceedings by sending back Labuschagne. In the same session, Root and Stokes struck as well to make it their session. Smith and Carey were taking the game away from them, until Anderson struck at the stroke of Tea and hunted down the pair, only to get beaten by the tail enders in the final session. The same pair that fought out of their skin to keep the side in the mix in the second innings of the first Test match has to do it all over again. But this time the position is even worse. Root and Malan need to bat in phases and make sure to keep an eye on running down the deficit. Another thrilling day of cricket awaits.

The Australians dominated Day 2 with the blade first and later even with the ball to end the day on a high. It started with Marnus Labuschagne's first ton against England. The stand-in skipper, Steven Smith, making 93. Carey with his maiden Test fifty. And to add on to the misery of the visitors, Starc and Neser extended their tally to 473/9 declare. Later the pair of Starc and Neser also had a great time with the ball. Starc got rid of Burns yet again in this series atleast it was not on the first ball this time. Soon after, Neser picked up his first-ever Test wicket, he couldn’t have asked for any better start to his international career. Steven Smith and his men would want to chip a couple wickets in the first session with the ball being pretty new.

Hello and welcome to Day 3 of the second Ashes Test match between Australia and England. As the game was abandoned on Day 2 due to a frightening lightning, the Australian bowlers would be itching to come back on the field but this afternoon the only thing lit up will be the sun. The hosts clearly hold the advantage coming into the moving day.
...Day 3, Session 1...

The rain gods come to the rescue of the Englishmen. Australia would be disappointed as they had to walk back to the pavilion because of some serious thunders around the Adelaide Oval. Something to cheer for the English fans as the play has been abandoned. It was a tough day with the ball earlier for the visitors and it that transcended with the blade as well, as they lost two wickets in just 8.4 overs into their innings. They would have lost Joe Root as well but luckily for them, the outside edge off his bat landed just short of his counterpart in the slip cordon. Australia, on the other hand, clearly hold the upper hand in this Test match. They will be hoping to come back stronger and better on the morning of Day 3. As far as England are concerned, they have a mountain to climb. But when the chips are down, that is when champions step up. And they have a pair in the middle which did a remarkable job in the second innings of the first Test, putting in a resounding fightback. Let's hope for a good day of cricket overall. Do join us for another intriguing day of Test cricket at 2.11 pm local time (3.41 am GMT). Cheers!

What a day it has been for Australia. It was Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith who started the second day with the blade. The former was sent back after he made his first century against England, early on in the day. And in no time, Australia even lost Travis Head and Cameron Green. Smith was very good with the blade today. He was supported well by Alex Carey who scored his maiden Test fifty for the Aussies and stitched a crucial sixth-wicket stand with Steven Smith of 91 runs. Although, at the stroke of Tea it was James Anderson who sent back both the batters back in the hut. The first session of the Day belonged to England, as they snatched up three wickets. But in the second session Australia were flying high at a brisk rate but Anderson made sure to pull things back for his side. This is when the tail-enders came out in the final session to bat for the hosts and England would've like to wrap things up early but that was not the case. Mitchell Starc and Michael Neser stitched a stand worth 58 runs which was followed by another short but impactful partnership of Starc and Richardson of 9-ball 25. Which hurt the English camp the most. After Jhye Richardson got caught behind, Steven Smith decided to call his players back in the hut and declared at 473/9.
UPDATE - 9.24 pm local (1054 GMT) - Not the news we were hoping for! The play has been abandoned and the umpires have called STUMPS on Day 2!

UPDATE - 9.13 pm local (1043 GMT) - OH NO! There is some serious lightning at the Adelaide Oval and so the umpires have asked the players to walk off the field. The good thing is that there is no rain at the moment. There is a precautionary cover placed over the pitch for now. Stay tuned for further updates.

Back of a length, outside off, moving away. And just as Neser released the ball, there was a huge flash around the ground. Malan leaves it alone though. The umpire have decided to stop the play for now.
Length and on off. Malan defends it out watchfully.
Good-length ball, outside off, moving away. Malan leaves it alone.

Length and on off. Root defends it to cover for a single. Good running this time. Root and Malan need to make sure to keep changing the strike here to get that left-hand/ right-hand combination in play.
Good length and shaping away, outside off, Malan shoulders his arms.
Fuller and outside off. Root leans in a drives it past mid off for a single.
Back of a length, outside off. Root gets back and blocks it to point.
Good length and on off. Root defends it out solidly.
Good-length ball, on off. Root defends it to the off side.
Length ball, on the pads, Root flicks it to square leg.
Slight drizzle is going on at the moment so the umpires are having a chat but they have decided to keep the play on for now.
Good-length ball, on off. Malan hangs back and blocks it out watchfully.
Three runs! On a length, outside off. Root stays back and guides it past the gully fielder. Nathan Lyon gives it a chase and keeps it down to three.

EDGED AND SHORT! Good-length ball, on the fourth stump line. Root hangs his bat out, as he looks to defend it out. The ball takes the outside edge and lands short of Steven Smith at second slip. A sigh of relief in the English camp.
Outside off, left alone by Root.
Joe Root, the skipper of England walks out to bat at number 4.

OUT! CAUGHT! Michael Neser gets his maiden Test wicket in his first over. His teammates love it. A full-length ball, around middle and leg. Haseeb Hameed stays inside the crease and flicks it aerially towards short mid-wicket. Mitchell Starc is placed at the right place and takes the simplest of catches to put the visitors in a spot of trouble already. You can call this a poor shot, or what was the need to play the ball in the air and so on. But this is where Smith's captaincy has to be given a nod. That man was strategically placed there, because Hameed has this habit of slicing the ball in the air, while getting across the line and looking to play on the leg side.
Commentary.Howout: c Mitchell Starc b Michael Neser

Commentary.Commentary: A very late withdrawal from Haseeb Hameed and Michael Neser has to wait for his first ball in Test cricket.
Full-length ball, on off. Hameed stays back and blocks it out towards gully off the outer half, as he gets squared up here.
The debutant, Michael Neser comes into the attack now.
A length ball, around off. Malan defends it out solidly. Third consecutive maiden for Jhye Richardson.
Good length and outside off. Malan leaves it alone for the keeper.
A length ball, around off. Malan defends it out watchfully.
A length ball sliding down leg. Malan leaves it alone. Carey moves to his right to collect the ball.
Good-length ball, outside off, the ball straightens a bit after hitting the deck. Malan stays back and shoulders his arms.
On a length, around off. Malan hangs back and taps it towards point.
Full length and outside off, Hameed looks to crunch it through the off side but miscues it. The ball takes the inner half and lands on the deck. First maiden for Mitchell Starc in this Test game.
Good length, outside off, nipping away. Hameed lets it go to the keeper.
Back of a length, on off. Hameed shoulders his arms. He trusts the bounce this time and sees the cherry go above the off pole.
Starc makes Hameed play this time. Good-length ball, on off. Hameed stays inside the crease and blocks it out solidly.
Touch fuller, outside off, some extra bounce off the deck. Haseeb Hameed does not chase this one.
Good-length ball, outside off, moving away. Hameed shoulders his arms and leaves it alone.

This is what mental games can do to you. In his 56-inning Test career, Rory Burns has opened for England in every inning. But here comes a small spice. In these 56 innings, Burns has NOT FACED the first ball of the team innings ONLY TWICE. And does it surprise you even one bit that both of those innings have come in this series? After that first-baller at the 'Gabba, Rory definitely seems to be nervous or not too keen to face the first ball of the innings. Or even more so, he seems to be hesitant to be facing Mitchell Starc up early. Position 1 or 2 does not matter too much while batting. But just the fact that RB seems to be thinking too much in his mind, has seen him tentative in this series so far. It is all in the mind, they say.
Another maiden over for Jhye Richardson. A length ball, around middle and off, shaping away. This is close to the body but Malan lets it go past him.
Full-length ball, outside off. Malan presses forward and defends it out watchfully.
On a length, outside off, shaping away. Malan shoulders his arms.
Another swinging away, on a fuller length. Malan does not chase this either.
On a length, moving away from the left-hander. Malan holds his defensive pose and lets the ball goes past him.
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away from the left-hander. Malan leaves it alone for the keeper.
A length ball, outside off, moving away. Hameed lets it go to the keeper. End of a successful over By Mitchell Starc.
Outside off, left alone by Hameed.
LEG BYE! Back of a length, around the hips. Malan misses his flick. The ball takes the thigh pads and runs towards fine leg. The batters collect a leg bye.
Nicely placed! Fuller and outside off. Hameed leans in and drives it through covers. Head recovers the ball near the ropes. The batters take three runs.
Malan gets off the mark. Good-length ball, outside off. Malan defends it towards cover and gets across for a single.
Dawid Malan walks in at number 3.

OUT! CAUGHT! Mitchell Starc sends back Rory Burns yet again in this Test series. Australia get the dream start they were looking for. Starc serves it quicker, back of a length, around off. Rory Burns shuffles across and looks to defend it out. The ball takes the outside edge and goes towards the second slip. Steven Smith is placed there who makes no mistake and pouches it comfortably.
Commentary.Howout: c Steven Smith b Mitchell Starc

Commentary.Commentary: BEATEN AGAIN! What a beauty! Jhye Richardson starts his spell with a maiden. A length ball, around off, nipping away. The ball beats the outside edge.
Full-length ball, on middle and leg. Haseeb Hameed squeezes it towards square leg. Not in the gap though.
Length and outside off, Hameed leaves it alone for the keeper.

BEATEN! Jhye Richardson causing early problems. On a length, outside off, nips in a touch. Haseeb Hameed looks to defend it out but misses. The ball zips past the outside edge. The keeper, Alex Carey catches it on his left.
A length ball, outside off. The ball seams away yet again. Hameed keeps the blade close to his body and lets it sail past him.
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Hameed leaves it for the keeper.
Who will bowl from the opposite end? Jhye Richardson it is.

FOUR! Rory Burns gets off the mark with a boundary. Fuller and on the pads, Rory Burns stays back and flicks it through mid-wicket. The ball races away into the fence. A positive start for the visitors, 7 runs coming off the first over.

Burns plays it very cautiously knowing what happened with him last time around! A full-length ball, around middle and leg. This one straightens a bit off the deck, Burns stays back and defends it to the leg side.
Good shot! A full-length ball, outside off. Hameed leans in and crunches it through covers. The fielder gives it a chase and pulls it back in time near the ropes. The batters take three runs.
That's better! Seems back off the deck. Good-length ball, on the fourth stump line. The ball nips in off the deck. Haseeb Hameed shoulders his arms and the ball goes off the off pole.
Length ball, way outside off, shaping away. Haseeb Hameed leaves it alone for the keeper.
Full-length ball, wide outside off. Haseeb Hameed leaves it alone. He would be glad that it was not on the stumps and did not trouble him.

We are back! Australian players stride out to the middle. Haseeb Hameed and Rory Burns are the openers for England. Mitchell Starc to open the bowling for Australia. England roughly have 44 overs to bat tonight and another 90 tomorrow - that means 134. Winning looks out of question, but if they manage to end today well, they can aim for a draw tomorrow, especially with Starc not fully fit.
... FOURTH INNINGS ...

AUSTRALIA DECLARE at 230/9! Steven Smith signals from the pavilion and asks his players to walk out of the field. Australia’s intention was clear to score runs at a brisk rate and due to that Head and Labuschagne holed out looking to go big. Green stayed out in the middle longer than expected and did well to extend their lead. And guess what? Once again it was the pair of Root and Malan, yes you read that right, this time it was with the ball. The combination took 4 wickets is total. The English batters have steep mountain to climb, as the target is 468 runs. They would hope to remain unscathed till the Tea break, as they will come out for their reply with the bat in a short while. All eyes would be on whether Mitchell Starc opens the bowling attack. Looking at the way he batted, do not think he will come out before Tea. Smith might use him for one spell under the lights and that might be it for him for the day. So that it gives him enough rest to bowl with fire tomorrow. Do not go anywhere, as an intruiging passage of play awaits.

OUT! CAUGHT! Dawid Malan bags his second wicket. This was a tossed up delivery, on middle. Jhye Richardson gets down on one knee and again goes for the slog sweep. This time, it goes off the top edge and just ahead of the keeper on the leg side. Jos Buttler gulps it down easily. And with that, Australia have declared their innings on 230. They lead by 467 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b Dawid Malan

Commentary.Commentary: SIX! What a shot! Right into the slot, on middle. Jhye Richardson gets low and slog-sweeps it over wide of long on for a biggie.
Tossed up, on off. Cameron Green gets down on one knee and drags it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Short and outside off. Jhye Richardson rocks back and hammers it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Very full, on the pads. Green flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.
Short and outside off. Cameron Green powers it down to long off for a couple of runs.
Outside off, Cameron Green swipes this one to long on for a single.
This is flicked to deep square leg for a single.
On the pads, worked to wide of long on for a single.
Jhye Richardson comes out to bat now. No other movement in the pavilion, that means no signs of declaration.

OUT! CAUGHT! Loopy ball, on middle. Mitchell Starc takes the aerial route and heaves it towards deep mid-wicket. The ball goes high up in the air. Ollie Pope dives in front of him and pouches it with both hands. Joe Root has two wickets now and Mitchell Starc departs.
Commentary.Howout: c Ollie Pope b Joe Root

Commentary.Commentary: On off, Starc cuts it to point.
Tossed up, fuller, outside off. Starc drives it through point for a brace.

DRINKS! Well, for all the criticism being poured on England for the last 15 days, it is time for change of direction. Really unnecessary from Starc and Australia. He is a bowler and not a batsman. And Australia do not require the extra cushion of runs. They are just playing for time, so that they can start bowling when the lights are on. And with a pulled muscle, do not understand why is Starc trying to play the big shots. And cannot understand even further why are Australia allowing him to be out there. In the quest of wanting to bowl under lights, they might end up losing their best bowler with the pink ball.
This is punched down to long off for a single.
Flatter, on leg. Green flicks it through mid-wicket for a run. Australia lead by 450 runs!
Slower through the air, on off. Starc drives it firmly to long off for a single.
Short and on middle. This time Green does get bat on it as he pulls it to fine leg for three runs.
Tossed up, on middle. Starc slog-sweeps it to deep square leg for a single.
Fuller, outside off. Starc looks to drive but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Mitchell Starc looks to be in some pain again, that six hurt him a lot but not his team. The physio come out now to have a look. He looks good to continue.
On the pads, flicked to square leg for a run.
SIX! BANG! In the slot, outside off. Mitchell Starc clears his front leg and tonks it ove long on for a maximum.
Flatter, on middle. Green wrists it to mid-wicket for a single.
On middle and leg, Cameron Green works it to wide of long on for a brace.
Mitchell Starc drops his bat on the ground and is holding is lower back. It looks a bit concerning for Australia, as they have to come out to bowl later in the evening.
On the pads, worked to mid-wicket for a single.
Full and outside off. Mitchell Starc has a big swing at it. But only manages it to work it to mid on. He drops his bat down and holds his back. Looks like he has hurt himself.
Flatter, outside off. Starc pushes it to long off for a single.

THREE BYES! Oh! That missed everything! Short and on middle, Cameron Green shuffles across and looks to pull but misses. Jos Buttler gets blinded by the batsman and fails to collect it as well. The ball goes over the stumps to fine leg for three byes.
On middle and leg, nudged on the leg side.
Tossed up, on middle. Green defends it out.
Loopy ball, outside off. Starc pushes it to covers for a single.
On off, Mitchell Starc heaves it to deep mid-wicket for a brace.
Floated, full and on off. Green defends it out watchfully.
Short and outside off, Starc punches it towards point for a single.
Around off, defended out.
Full and on off. Starc defends it out.
Looped up, full and on off. Starc prods and defends it back to the bowler.
Floated, on a length, wide of off. Green goes back and guides it through backward point. The batters take three before the fielder cuts it out.
Around off, Green helps it through square leg for a single.
Flatter and short, outside off, Starc cuts it through point for a run.
Short and outside off, Starc looks to chase it away but misses.
Touch short and on middle. Green works it through square leg for a single now.
Full and on off. Green defends it out.
Touch short and on leg. Green pulls it through mid-wicket for a brace. Good running here.

OUT! DRAGGED ON! Another one bites the dust! On a length, around off, turning in. Carey stays on the back foot and looks to cut it away to the off side. The ball takes the inside edge and goes onto the disturb the stumps behind. Australia lose their seventh wicket now. Mitchell Starc walks out to bat.
Commentary.Howout: b Joe Root

Commentary.Commentary: Short and wide outside off. Green stands back and cuts it towards point for a single.
Flatter, around off. Carey goes back and cuts it through point for a single.
FOUR! Up and over! Fuller and on off. Carey gets under it and lofts it towards long on. A couple of bounces and into the ropes.
On a length, sliding down leg. Carey leaves it alone.
Tossed up, full and on off. Carey presses forward to defend it out.
Tossed up, on off. Green defends it out watchfully to the off side. A wicket and just 3 runs off it. A good over by Malan.
A sharp googly, around middle and off. Green goes back and defends it out safely.
Carey gets off the mark! Full and on off. Carey works it to long on for a single.
Alex Carey is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Dawid Malan gets his first Test wicket and this is only the third time Marnus Labuschagne slipped out to a leg-spinner. Floated, full and on off. Marnus Labuschagne gets low and slog-sweeps it to deep mid-wicket. He does not get the desired distance on it and Ben Stokes will never drop such sitters. He pouches it comfortably and Marnus Labuschagne's knock comes to an end. A crucial breakthrough by Dawid Malan.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Stokes b Dawid Malan

Commentary.Commentary: Around off, Green pushes it to cover for a single.
Floated, full and on middle. Marnus Labuschagne sweeps it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Full and on the pads, Green nudges it to mid-wicket.
Full and on off. Malan drives it through covers for a brace now.
Fuller, on off. Green pushes it to cover. Haseeb Hameed misfields, the batters were looking for a single, but Hameed was quick to rectify his mistake and restricts a single here.
Length and on the pads, Marnus Labuschagne clips it to the leg side for a single. FIFTY up for Marnus Labuschagne. He truly enjoys batting against England.
Length and on leg. Green tucks it behind square for a single.
Full length, on off. Marnus Labuschagne pushes it firmly through cover for a single.
Floated and on middle. Green defends it to the leg side. A good over by Malan.
On off, defended out.
A dot now! Flatter and around off. Green works it towards point.
Tossed up, around off. Marnus Labuschagne pushes it to point for a single.
Full and around leg, Green goes back and flicks it to square leg for a run now.
Short and on off. Marnus Labuschagne punches it to point for a single.

Oh dear. Here comes the time when Joe Root starts to look for part-timers. DAWID MALAN is the first of them. Root himself cannot bowl as he was off the field for a long time and given the fact that Robinson was forced to bowl offies, shows the desperation and frustration in the English camp right now. And the problem is - Root is not only looking for an Aussie declaration, he is also looking for a way to improve England's overrate. Hence the offies and leggies.
On a good length, on off. Cameron Green blocks it out.
Fuller in length, on middle. Pushed to mid off.
On a length, on middle. Cameron Green works it to deep square leg for a brace. Australia now lead by 400 runs!
NO BALL! Short ball, on middle. Cameron Green lets it be. Ollie Robinson oversteps and the umpire signals a no ball.
Short of a length, on middle. Marnus Labuschagne slaps it to deep cover for a single.
Length ball, on middle. Cameron Green tucks it to square leg for a run.
Back of a length, on off. Marnus Labuschagne nudges it on the leg side for a single.
Good length, on top of off. Green comes across yet again and defends it to the leg side.
Full and outside off, Green leans in and drives it towards cover-point.
Length ball, around off, nips is a bit. Green shuffles across and helps it back to the bowler.
Fuller and outside off, Green coves his stumps and defends it out to cover.
Good length, on off. Green blocks it out watchfully.
Full length, on middle and leg. Green shuffles across and flicks it through mid-wicket for a brace.
Play and a miss! Short ball, on middle. Marnus Labuschagne looks to hook it away but misses.
A dot now! Full length, on the pads, Marnus Labuschagne clips it to short mid-wicket.
Fuller and on off. Green tucks it towards mid on for another single.
Length and on the pads, Marnus Labuschagne flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! Up and over! Full-length ball, on off. Marnus Labuschagne walks down the pitch and lofts it over mid on to bag a boundary. 150 is up for Australia. The lead moves to 390.
Ollie Robinson goes past the outside edge another time! Length ball, landing on off and nipping away. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend it out but misses.
Full and on leg, Marnus Labuschagne flicks it through square leg for a single.
Good length and outside off. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend it out but misses.
A length ball, on off. Marnus Labuschagne guides it towards backward point for a brace.

OH DEAR! Marnus Labuschagne was a goner here. A length ball, outside off. Cameron Green shuffles across and defends it to backward point. He hesitates for a single and Marnus Labuschagne was late in his charge to the danger end. Ollie Pope collects the ball and has a shy at the striker's end but misses. Marnus Labuschagne had given up and way not anywhere near the popping crease.
On a length, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne defends it to the off side and rotates the strike.
A dot now! Good length, around off. Marnus Labuschagne defends it to the leg side.
Cameron Green walks out to bat.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ben Stokes takes a stunning catch in the deep to send back Travis Head. His entertaining innings comes to an end. Ollie Robinson picks up his second wicket and breaks an important partnership this time. Short ball, around off. Head stays back and thinks of riding the bounce. He hooks to deep square leg. Ben Stokes runs to his left and takes a good low diving catch to his left. He gets there in time.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Stokes b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Length and on off. Head defends it out watchfully.
SWING AND A MISS! Length ball, outside off, angled across the left-hander. Travis Head stays on the back foot and looks to cut it away but misses.
Fuller and on off. Head digs it out back to the bowler.
Full and outside off. Head throws his bat at it and gets an inside edge towards mid on.
On a good length, on off. Marnus Labuschagne pushes it to point for a single.
Ollie Robinson to bowl from the other end.
TWO RUNS! FIFTY for Travis Head. He is scoring for fun here. Short ball, on off. Head pulls it through mid-wicket for a brace.
FOUR! Top shot! A full-length ball, on off. Head hits it past the bowlers head and into the fence at long off.
Angled into the pads, Head looks to nudge it to the leg side but misses.
Length ball, around leg. Head stays back and looks to flick it away but misses. The ball meets the keeper on the bounce to his left. Comes off the hips this time.
Good-length ball, on off. Travis Head blocks it out to cover.

Nice work by Ollie Pope in the field. A length ball, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne hangs back and punches it through cover-point. The ball races away past the diving attempt of the fielder. Ollie Pope gives it a chase and slides foward to pull the ball back in play. Save a run for his side here, as the batters run three.
We are ready for the middle session! England players stride out to the middle. Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head jog out as well to resume their innings. Chris Woakes to start with the ball.
... DAY 4, SESSION 2 ...

England needed quick wickets and their frontline pacers - James Anderson and Stuart Broad provided exactly that. The visitors scalped two wickets in quick succession and had their opponents under control. Jos Buttler had a roller-coaster match behind the stumps but that two catches off Marcus Harris and Steven Smith will do a world of good. England kept hitting probing lines and lengths around the off pole and restricted Australia to keep the scoreboard ticking. After the first hour it looked like the session would belong to England but Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head had other plans as they started to counter attack. Will England manage to scap the remaining wickets quickly? Or will Australia declare the innings and ask England to come out and bat before Tea under the lights? Do join us at 5.40 pm local (6.10 am GMT) to find out.

The first hour of the day's play was a scratchy one for Australia. The nightwatchman, Michael Neser couldn't stay for long and then Marcus Harris followed him to the pavilion too. Steven Smith had a good first innings and was given a lifeline as he was dropped on a duck but couldn't stay for long as he fell cheaply off a nothing ball. Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head since then started to free their arms a little and scored runs at a brisk rate. The duo has done well to remain unscathed and depsite of a nervy first hour, they have pulled back things nicely in the final hour and have put Australia in a commanding position.

What a good comeback this is by Australia! Session score - 27 overs, 89 runs, 3 wickets! The hosts have stretched their lead by 371 runs now and Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head hold the key for them while the others will try to tick alongside them. They did lost 3 wickets but they won't be in a panic state here as they are just 29 runs short of breaching the 400-run mark and they will be looking to pile as many runs as they can to post an unassailable total on the board.
Length and on off. Travis Head defends it to cover.
Aggressive running here! Touch short, on leg. Head clips it to fine leg. Travis Head calls for two and gets two runs.
Fuller and on middle. Marnus Labuschagne stays back and clips it through mid-wicket for three runs.
Good length and outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone for the keeper.
Short of a length, outside off. Travis Head pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! In the gap, timed to perfection. Length ball, on the pads. Head flicks it through square leg for a boundary.
Outside off, left alone by Marnus Labuschagne.
FOUR! Runs are coming in thick and fast for the hosts. Short ball, around off. Marnus Labuschagne stands back and pulls it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
On off, defendedout watchfully.

Marnus Labuschagne is just home! The dive save him though. Full and on the pads. Marnus Labuschagne flicks it to deep square leg. Ollie Pope comes out with a nice effort near the ropes to save the boundary. He throws it flat towards the keeper. Jos Buttler collects it well and removes the stumps. Marnus Labuschagne dives and gets himself insde the crease safely and the replays suggest the same, as the umpire takes it upstairs.
Length, around middle and off. Head defends it back to the bowler. Another no ball by Stokes, this is his third in two overs.
Fuller, on off. Head clips it to mid-wicket.
FOUR! Smacked! Short and outside off. Head hangs back and pulls it to deep square leg for a boundary. The lead moves to 353 for Australia.
Touch short and on off. Marnus Labuschagne drags his pull shot to mid-wicket.

Play and a miss! This has happened a several times today for England. A length ball, around off, nips away off the deck sharply. Marnus Labuschagne looks to drive it through the cover region but gets beaten.
Touch short and outside off. Marnus Labuschagne shoulders his arms at it.
Good length, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone for the keeper.
Full length and on off. Marnus Labuschagne gets it off the outer half aerially towards point. But the ball lands in front of the fielder.
Good length and angled into the pads, Head stays back and flicks it behind square on the leg side for a single.
Change from both ends. Stuart Broad (8-3-16-1) comes into the attack. He replaces James Anderson.
Length and on the pads, Head flicks it to mid-wicket for a single. 12 runs coming off it. Ben Stokes should aim going full, rather than continuing with his short ball ploy.
FOUR! This is tunring out to be a big over for Australia. Slightly short and on off. Head stays back and pulls it through square leg for a boundary.
WIDE! A sharp bouncer, around leg. Head ducks under this one and the umpire signals a wide.
Length, around off, nipping in. Marnus Labuschagne flicks it to mid-wicket for a single. The stand moves to 50.
NO BALL! Second no ball off the over, as Ben Stokes oversteps. Length and on off. Marnus Labuschagne defends it out watchfully.
Back of a length, around the hips. Head tucks it to square leg for a single.
Short and outside off. Head cuts it to cover-point but straight to the fielder.
Slightly short and on off. Marnus Labuschagne swivels and pulls it to deep square leg for a single. The umpire signals a no ball, as the bowler oversteps.
Short and on off. Head pulls it through mid-wicket for a single. 100 comes up for Australia.
Ben Stokes is brought into the attack. He replaces Ollie Robinson.
Short and outside off, nips away a bit. Marnus Labuschagne is happy to leave that one alone.
BEATEN! Good length, around off. Marnus Labuschagne gets squared up as he looks to defend it out and gets beaten on the outside edge.
Back of a length, outside off, nips in late. Marnus Labuschagne shoulders his arms.
On off, defended out.

FOUR! EDGY! Just wide of Root at first slip. Back of a length, around off. Marnus Labuschagne keeps the blade close to his body. The ball takes the outside edge and goes past the attempt of Root for a boundary. Joe Root still looks to be in some kind of pain. Maybe he was a bit hesitant before diving for the catch. Bizarre, bizarre captaincy - whoever it be - Ben Stokes or Joe Root. You can place two slips for Chris Woakes - but when your best bowlers of the afternoon are bowling - Anderson and Broad - you have one slip. Why this partiality? Even though Australia have a big lead, if England can stop them under 150, who knows, we may be in for a miracle. For that, they need wickets.
Good length, wide outside off. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it alone.
Full toss and outside off. Marnus Labuschagne reaches out and slashes it towards sweeper cover for another single.
Tossed up, full and on off. Head works it to mid on for another run.
Very full and on leg. Marnus Labuschagne clips it to square leg for a run.
Full and on middle. Head comes down the track and works it towards mid on for a single. These are easy runs for Australia.
Short and on the pads, Marnus Labuschagne clips it to fine leg for a single.
Fuller and on off. Head flicks it towards mid on and gets a single.

A huge blow for England! Jonny Bairstow will be on the field to replace Root. Have England lost their part-time spinner as well?

It was yet another collapse for the visitors. Even this time Root was expected to carry too much weight on his shoulders. The wicketless first session on Day 3 was like a light at the end of the tunnel, but once Root departed, the old friend, darkness was back around the English camp, as they only mustered 86 runs and lost 8 wickets to their say with the blade. England got lucky with Warner’s departure last evening and still have a steep task ahead of them. Will they be able to restrict the Aussies below the 150-run mark? Or will the hosts double their lead? Another thrilling day of Test cricket awaits.

The Aussies hold a strong grip over the advantage coming into Day 4. After coming out to bat last evening, as Smith didn't opt to enforce the follow-on, the hosts have a lead of 282 runs with nine wickets to play with. Their only aim would be to bat the first two sessions, only to come back and bowl under the floodlights just like they did on Day 2.

Hello and a warm welcome to all! It is time for Day 4 of the second Ashes Test match. The moving day just like the name moved at a fierce pace. Australia clearly have their noses in front and would look forward to put on a mammoth target for the visitors.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Right then. Thursday - Australia. Friday - Australia. Saturday - Australia. England need to pack a punch from somewhere. One such divine help might come to them on Sunday, with rain forecast for the major part of the day. But they cannot just rely on the weather. They need to try and get Australia all out under 150 to give themselves some sort of a chance. Australia will be looking to get their batsmen in form - Harris and Green especially, to have better batting efforts in the coming Tests. Expect them to score quickly and declare somewhere around Tea to try and maximize the night session. Join us then, on Sunday, 19th December, 2021, for Day 4 of the second Ashes Test, from the Adelaide Oval. The first ball will be bowled at 2.30 pm local (0400 GMT), but the build-up will begin well in advance. So tune in early. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

One expected the Aussies to enforce the follow-on especially with the lights on and Sunday's forecast reading grey but Smith either wanted to give his bowlers some rest, or wanted to put Australia in a non-losing position or just wanted to give his batsmen some time to get into form. Marcus Harris has certainly made use of that small opportunity and started well, taking Australia to a flier. In the back of his mind, he knows that in all likelihood, he will be boxed out by Usman Khawaja from the Boxing Day Test, but he can only try and score runs. Selection is not his headache. England bowled without much fire or rhythm and even the in-form Ollie Robinson looked tired. This is what happens when one plays back-to-back Test matches with too many overs of bowling and little rest.

He may not play cricket for a whole year but still could come back and take a 3-fer, 4-fer or a Michelle in a day/night Test. Yes, that is Mitchell, with the surname Starc. Good bowling or not, he got another 4-fer to his name, but to be honest, Australia's really good bowlers on the day were Nathan Lyon and Cameron Green, whose combined figures of 38-14-82-5 choked the opposition. And Starc benefitted. That second session of play hurt England badly and they are now in another massive hole - in this Test, in this series and perhaps, in Test cricket in general.

Often, Day 3 is called as the moving day in Test cricket. And it has moved along at a frenetic pace with the third innings underway. The Aussies are on top, but at Dinner, it did not seem so that way. Dawid Malan and skipper Joe Root were rattling along nicely and having spent a wicketless session, it felt like we were in for a good fightback from England. However, just as it happened in their second innings at the 'Gabba, the same story unfolded. Root could not quite control himself from running one down to third man off Green and after that, found his opposition's bowlers running his batsmen down in next to no time. England were 150/2 before that shot - 232 balls later, they had lost 8/86. The middle order collapsed yet again and the question arose once more - A daunting team with white ball, not quite good enough in whites?

End of a terrific day for Australia. Yes, they would have wished to have both openers unscathed at the crease but to be 282/1 in effect makes a very good reading. England will be happy with that run out of Warner but they know, they have a mountain to climb.

OUT! RUN OUT! Oh dear! Absolute chaos in the middle and it is David Warner who has to walk back to the pavilion! This was a flatter ball, on leg. Marcus Harris tucks it to square leg and takes off for a run. Warner at the non-striker's end is in two minds whether to run or not and by the time he goes for it he was halfway down the pitch and Stuart Broad had thrown the ball to Jos Buttler. So Warner decides to run back to the bowler's end but Harris had already reached the non-striker's end and the former pulls out in the end. Buttler whips the bails off and Warner takes the long walk back to the hut. To be honest, Warner has sacrificed his wicket here. If he wished, he could have scampered back to the non-striker's end and made it in before Harris. But he knew that it was his call and hence, his mistake, so did not bother to put in too much effort once he saw Harris fully committed. Team spirit.
Commentary.Howout: run out (Stuart Broad / Jos Buttler)

That ends the coverage from the second Test match of the Ashes. Australia have taken a 2-0 lead in the series and are favorites now to retain the urn. But England cannot be ruled out yet. They will look to fighback and give their rivals a hard time. The third Test match will be played at Melbourne Cricket Ground on 26th of December from 10.30 am local (11.30 pm GMT, previous day). Do join us for that match. Till then, goodbye and cheers!

Marnus Labuschagne, Player of the Match, says that credit to Warner was batting so well. Mentions that he tried to absorb the pressure but says that when one has Warner in a team, it becomes easier. Tells that he congratulated himself on how he played. Adds that to get the win is very special and it is important to not get the foot off the pedal. Tells that playing with Neser and Richardson is brilliant and they are both unique and are brilliant in their own forms. Says that all his wishes are coming true and mentions that getting his first Ashes ton is special but is disappointed that he didn't make it into a big one despite getting a few chances.

Steven Smith, the skipper of Australia, says that he was not nervous and he enjoyed himself out there in the middle. Mentions that Jos Buttler played really well out there, he showed some resilience along with Woakes and Ollie Robinson. But they had to stay calm and wait for the right ball to get the wickets. Mentions that, David Warner and Marnus Labuschagne's partnership set things up for them and Mitchell Starc led the attack very well. He hit the right lengths and kept attacking the batsman. Also, he adds, Cameron Green was not supposed to bowl today as they had to manage his workload, but had to bowl a few overs because the situation demanded. He further adds that, Marcus Harris has been in the nets and should not overthink it and should just trust the process. Concludes by saying that, they have entertaining people in these difficult Covid time as the protocols are very high and says that they will go about doing their business as good as they can.

Joe Root, the England skipper, says that it was a rough day yesterday. Adds that they did not bowl the right lengths in the first innings and they had to bowl fuller, which they did in the second innings and managed to get wickets. Adds that it was disappointing because they made the same mistake four years ago. Mentions that they need to be better and they still have a chance to come back in the series. Further adds that they are confident and have to be confident and they will be hoping not the repeat the same mistakes again. On being asked about Buttler's innings, Joe Root, says that they need that kind of attitude, and mindset throughout the series.
Stay tuned for Presentation...

Earlier, Australia set the tone in the first innings itself by posting 473 runs on the board where David Warner, Marnus Labuschagne, Steven Smith, Alex Carey made significant contributions whereas the lower-order too made handy runs before Steven Smith decided to declare. England faced collapse as they went from 150-2 to 236 all out where only Dawid Malan and Joe Root scored the bulk of runs for them. Steven Smith didn't enforce the follow on and his side added another 230 runs giving England a target of 467 runs. England faced the same issue as they lost wickets in heap and except Jos Buttler and Chris Woakes, no one showed grit and determination and in the end they lost by 275 runs.

It looked like Australia would quickly wrap things up in the second session as they needed just 4 wickets to win but they had to toil hard to get the remaining wickets. With the new ball too, the bowlers didn't get much out of it until Jhye Richardson bowled a peach of a delivery to dismiss Chris Woakes. The bowlers were made to work very hard to get the wickets and only got one more wicket before Tea. With just 2 wickets needed in the final session, it was always easy for them to get it as they had to bowl it under lights and only had Jos Buttler as a challenge in front of them but he himself made it easy for them by knocking himself out and then Jhye Richardson made his day special by scalping the final wicket, picking up his maiden five-wicket haul in Test cricket and giving Australia a victory.

Drawing the Test match was always an improbable task for England but credit to Jos Buttler for showing such grit, temperament, determination and an impressive rearguard. He faced 207 balls to give his side a chance to draw this Test but all the hard-work ended as Buttler hit the wicket himself. Chris Woakes too batted brillaintly and built a 61-run stand with him but got out. Ollie Robinson too showed a bit of a fight but Nathan Lyon had him before the Tea break and England had only 2 wickets in their tank especially with final session being played under the lights. Once Jos Buttler fell, it was just a matter of time for the Australian pacers to get the final wicket.

There it is! Australia have scalped those 2 wickets in no time. It fits perfectly as well as Jhye Richardson bags a fifer to his name. He is the man of the hour at the moment. Maiden five-wicket haul for him in Test cricket. Got a chance to prove himself with Hazlewood and Cummins out of this Test, he showed his worth and how. Australia have conquered Gabba and Adelaide now and have a 2-0 lead in the series.

OUT! That's it! This ends England's fight! Jhye Richardson gets the final wicket of James Anderson and gets his 5-wicket haul. A short delivery, on the body. James Anderson jumps and gets a thick outside edge towards gully. Cameron Green there holds on to that comfortably. AUSTRALIA WIN BY 275 runs!

Cannot help but liken this rearguard action from Jos Buttler to the one showed by South Africa's Faf du Plessis 9 years ago, at this very ground. Faf had stayed unbeaten on 110 from a mammoth 376 balls, spending 466 minutes at the crease, ensuring that his team did not lose. Buttler has just crossed the 200-mark here in terms of balls faced. A key difference is that Faf had AB de Villiers to see off nearly two sessions. Here, it has been Buttler trusting his own abilities and shepherding the lower order. Either ways, magnificent to watch. Make no mistake - Australia have thrown everything that they possibly could have - but Buttler and England's lower order have been defiantly stubborn. Counting the overs now - 24 to go after this.

The hosts could have sealed the deal here as Tea was extended since only 2 wickets were needed. But they still managed to grab two wickets in the session. They are just two away from extending their lead in this series. Nathan Lyon has been on the money this time, he has served those flighted deliveries, on perfect line and length and made the batters struggle. They will have to go into the final session of the day to pick up the two wickets. The final session will be played under lights and it will get more tough for English batters to battle out. Will Jos Buttler fight it out for this side? Or is it only a matter of time that Australia scalp the final 2 wickets? Do join us at 7.50 pm local (0920 GMT) for the final session which promises to be a thriller.

Jos Buttler and Chris Woakes started off right where they left off from. They were on top in the first half-hour of the session, but Woakes fell soon to a ripper by Jhye Richarson. Ollie Robinson did well to hang in there but he too failed to hold on and was dismissed by Nathan Lyon! Jos Buttler is still out there in the middle and has been terrific and has shown immense grit and determination.

Another session, and yet again it belongs to Australia. But, England survive! Australia's hunt for the wicket continues! Probably this session was not completely dominated by the hosts, as England were as solid as a rock in the session courtesy to Jos Buttler who has batted for over four hours now. They have managed to scrape through the second session, Australia would be a little frustrated here, but they still have one full session to grab the final 2 wickets.

The Hosts started the day brilliantly and had the perfect first hour. Pink ball specialist, Mitchell Starc grabbed the wicket of Ollie Pope and sent him back early in the session. Nathan Lyon bagged the prized scalp of Ben Stokes, after reviewing the LBW decision. Since then, they have not managed to get any wicket. Nathan Lyon has missed his lengths on several occasions, going shorter most of the times, and has not got the desired result, but however, he has been able to extract a lot of turn. Just before the end of the first session, we saw Marnus Labuschagne roll his arm over, and bowled a beauty of an over. They will have the new ball in the second session and the seamers will look forward to wrapping it up in the session itself. Join us at 5.10 pm local (0710 GMT) for the middle session.

After losing Ollie Pope early, Ben Stokes showed some resilience and looked pretty conservative with the bat, but eventually fell to Nathan Lyon. Jos Buttler and Chris Woakes have done well and have steadied the ship after that. England will be hoping this partnership to carry on till the end of the day, and if it does, then boy will that be a miracle here. Still, a mountain to climb here for the visitors. They will try to come out and do exactly the same.

RUN OUT MISSED! Oops, my dear - what happened there? Loopy delivery, on middle. Chris Woakes advanced down the pitch and looked to flick. But he missed and got hit on his pads. Now, Woakes was busy searching for the ball and was looking to his left. But the ball had rolled towards silly point. An alert Marcus Harris at silly point quickly collected the ball and had a shy at the striker's end, but he missed. Woakes was nowhere in the picture! This reminds me of an Ashes Test in Perth, 2006, at the WACA. Geraint Jones, the then keeper of England, had lunged to defend a delivery against Shane Warne. The ball went off his pads to Ricky Ponting at silly point and the entire Aussie contingent went up in an appeal for a bat-pad. But the ever-alert Ponting quickly threw the ball at the striker's end to catch Jones short and ran him out!

England faced yet another collapse on Day 4. It was integral for them that their openers remain unscathed till Stumps and have an outside chance to draw the match. But that wasn't the case as they lost 4 wickets which includes their pillars - Dawid Malan and Joe Root. Joe Root went through a lot of pain but kept batting and showed fighting spirit but in the final minutes of Day 4, he got out and walked off in disbelief. Shouldn't be long before Australian bowlers breathe fire unless we are in for a surprise.

Australia batted one and a half sessions on Day 4 and in that, they managed to pile a plethora of runs and set a target of 468 runs for England. The bowlers have done their job picking up 4 wickets and Australia are now on top of this context. The bowlers would look to wrap things quickly by taking the remaining wickets and take an unassailable lead of 2-0 in the 5-match series.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 5 of the second Test match between Australia and England. Australia just need 6 wickets to win this Test and would look to wrap things up quickly as they don't have to deal with Dawid Malan and Joe Root as well who have been the best English batsmen on this tour so far. While England would hope that Ben Stokes could repeat his Headingley performance and take this match to the final session for a solid finish.
... DAY 5, SESSION 1 ...

That is it from Day 4 then! Australia are well in control here and a win for them looks the likeliest result. However, cricket is a game of uncertainties and if England can find batters to hang in there, who knows, we could see a draw and if that happens, it will definitely not be less than a win for the visitors. Do join us for Day 5 action at 1430 local (0400 GMT). But as you all know you can join us early for the build-up. Cheers!

Yet another collapse was on the horizon for England, but Root and Stokes managed to steady the ship in the middle, until the last over when Root nicked one back to the slips. Stokes looked pretty conservative with the blade and he has a huge task to overcome on the final day. Chasing down the target won’t be in their mind at all. To be honest, to pull out a draw out of this fixture isn’t going to be an easy task at all with just 6 wickets in hand. England would need more than the rub of green to take out something out of this game. Steven Smith was smart with his bowling combinations. All the bowlers probed good lines and lengths but could not find success. But the pink-ball specialist, Starc, comes out with a ripper to get his a step closer to the finish line.

A hard-fought battle by the visitors, but the hosts enjoyed plenty of success. Malan and Burns after being looked to have settled in the middle negotiated the first half-hour of the final session really well against the consistent attack of Lyon, combined with Green, Neser and Richardson. After several attempts, Lyon got the outside edge of Malan, but Smith ended up dropping that one at slips. A rare, dropped catch from Australia’s point of view, but Malan could not make the most of his reprieve, and slipped out soon. Burns followed his team-mate back to the pavilion. Courtesy of Jhye Richardson and Michael Neser.

A top session for the Aussies. Mitchell Starc comes out with a hammer blow in the final over to get rid of Root at the stroke of STUMPS. Australia bagged three wickets in this session and gave away only 62 runs. They surely would’ve liked to take a couple more scalps and extend the play to end the game this evening itself but that was not the case.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! The way Steven Smith was jumping in joy after the catch was taken just shows how big and how pleased are the Aussies with this wicket. Exactly what they would have wanted before Stumps. Either the wicket of Root or Stokes, the former preferably and they have got it. Starc the provider again. Really have to feel sorry for Root. He was battling through a lot of pain, he just had the 4 balls to get through on Day 4 but he falls. He could have left this one alone though but probably the left-arm around angle does him in. This lands outside off, and holds its line. Root looks to defend, it was well outside off. He does so inside the line. The ball goes off the outside edge and the keeper does the rest. He walks back and so do the other plays as THAT IS STUMPS ON DAY 4!
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Carey b Mitchell Starc

Commentary.Commentary: Length and on off, Root keeps it out.
Flatter and on off. Stokes defends it out and sees off the penultimate over.
Quicker and flatter, just outside off. Stokes defends it out on his back foot.
Touch short and on off. Stokes defends it out without any hesitation.
Looped up, around off. Stokes blocks it out.
Short and outside off. Stokes goes back and blocks it out watchfully.
Floated, full and outside off. Stokes comes across and blocks it into the deck.
On middle, defended.
NIcely drive! Fuller and outside off, Root drives it through covers for a couple more.

Well played! Fuller and on the pads, this is clipped through square leg for two. Smart bowling from Starc. By bringing in short leg, he planted the seed of a short ball in Joe Root's mind. But then, he went full. However, given the class of Root, he was up for it and played it well. He is still struggling to run between the wickets and that is something Australia will also notice.
Angled into middle, Root looks to defend but it goes off the inner half on the leg side.
Good length and outside off again, left alone.
All we can do is feel for Joe Root. He is on the field with a lot of pain. The physio is out to have a look. The players are covering Joe Root as he sorts out his guard now.

That has hurt! OUCH! Root is in serious pain! Length and on middle, this one comes back in. Root looks to defend but gets an inside edge and it hits him near the crouch area. Root was hit in the abdomen this morning and could not take the field for a while. And now, he has been hit in an area where no physio or doctor can do anything, apart from give a few comforting words.
On the stumps, blocked.
On the stumps this time, not a lot of turn. Kept out.
BEATEN! That is another beauty! Lyon has been excellent. On off, this one turns away. Stokes looks to defend but is beaten.
Solid again! On the stumps, kept out.
On off, this is pushed to mid off.
A single as this is worked with the turn through square leg.
That was close! An error of judgement from Stokes! This is angled into the pads, he thought it would slip down leg and hence, lets it go. He gets hit on the pads. Probably too high.
On middle, Stokes keeps it out.
Shorter and on off, Stokes hops and keeps it out.
Cut him into half! That is a beauty! Length and outside off, this one jags back in. Stokes is cut into half as he tries to put bat on ball.
Half an appeal but turned down! Shorter and on the body, Stokes looks to nudged it on the leg side. There is a noise as the ball passes the batter. Carey takes it and appeals but turned down.
On middle, Stokes keeps it out well.
Again! Big turn! On off and spins back in. Root looks to play it on the leg side but no connection.
Sharp turn again! This lands outside off and spins back in. Root goes back to defend but gets hit on the pads.
Slightly flatter, this one turns away. Stokes guides it to point for one.
On middle, Stokes defends.
On middle, this is worked through square leg for one.
Good keeping! This lands on middle and then spins back down the leg side sharply. Root looks to flick but misses. Carey does well to move across and take it.
On middle, kept out.
Slightly fuller and on middle, it is pushed to mid on.
Back of a length and on off, Stokes hangs back and plays it on the off side.
Yet another one outside off, Stokes covers his off pole and shoulders arms to this one.
A lot fuller than the last ball, Stokes still hangs back and defends.
Just outside off, Stokes shuffles across and leaves it alone.
A good ball to end by Lyon! Really good start from him. On middle, this also lands and spins away. Stokes hangs back to defend but it goes off the outer half through point for one.
Lovely nut yet again! This lands on middle and then turns away. Stokes looks to defend but it goes more off the outer half on the off side.
Flatter and on the stumps, Stokes goes back and puts bat on ball.

Loopy ball on middle, Stokes lunges and defends it out.
The GOAT (Nathan Lyon) is back into the attack. His figures read 10-2-24-0 so far.
Yet another dot! On off, back of a length, Root gets on top of the bounce and plays it to point.
Good length and on off, Root plays it with soft hands towards point.
Angling away from off, Root leaves it alone.
On middle, played back to the bowler.
Attacks the middle pole, Root stays rooted to his crease and plays it back to the bowler.
Length and on off, Root defends.

Drop and run! On off, Root plays it towards point and takes one.
On middle, Root works it towards mid on.
Back of a length and on off, Root stands tall and keeps it out.

Meanwhile, at the 'Gabba, Saqib Mahmood, one of England's bright future prospects, is running riot, having picked up 4 wickets in 11 balls! He can be a good option for England, at least in their bowling department. This series is too long, you see.

Not sure what Stokes was doing there! On middle, Stokes looks to defend, it goes off the outer half towards point. Stokes was busy admiring his stroke. Root was calling for a run, Stokes realized later and then completes it.
Outside off, Stokes lets it go to the keeper.
Another delivery, on a back of a length. Blocked well.
On middle, Root works it to mid on.

Aha... who let Uzzie out, who? Who? One of the Aussie players is getting the dirt off the spikes from his shoes and there is a delay. Usman Khawaja, who is on as a substitute, perhaps for Mitchell Starc, puts his dancing shoes on and entertains the Adelaide crowd at the boundary! The crowd loves it

On off, defended.

On the fuller side, Stokes lunges and tries to block but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
On off, Stokes hangs back and defends.

Outside off, Stokes leaves it alone.

Steven Smith keeps his eyes on the ball and takes a sharp catch low to his right. Ben Stokes will be the new man in.

DRINKS! Quite an important phase coming up! Around 17 overs left in the day's play and England really can't afford to lose a wicket. Australia on the other hand, have bowled really well and have to continue the good work. They would love Root's wicket before Stumps. Can they get it?

OUT! LBW! Michael Neser you beauty! He gets the big wicket of Dawid Malan and Neser picks up his first wicket of the innings. This is the second time we are witnessing a reprieve not lasting long today. Earlier in the day, Smith was dropped once but did not last long after that, while Malan, who was just dropped by Smith an over before, falls on the next ball he faces. A length ball, around off, nips in sharply off the deck. Malan is stuck inside his crease and gets rapped on the pads. Neser appeals and the umpire raises his dreaded finger. Top class stuff from the bowler. Malan gives it a thought and takes the review eventually. The RTS shows no bat is involved. The Ball Tracker shows three reds and Malan has to walk back to the pavilion.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Michael Neser

We are back for the final session! Australian players stride out to the middle. Dawid Malan and Rory Burns walk out to bat as well who have their work cut out and are battling to survive. Spin to start the final session as Nathan Lyon comes on to operate now.
... DAY 4, SESSION 3 ...

The hosts will want to get at least 3-4 wickets by Stumps tonight to try and avert any possible fightback tomorrow. However, there is nothing much on the pitch yet and if the batsmen apply themselves, like Malan and Root did in the first dig, runs can be scored. Around 36 overs left in the day for survival. We are heading into a break but you can just switch tabs and check out what is happening in the Big Bash game between Brisbane Heat and Sydney Thunder. But do not forget to join us back at 7.30 pm local (0900 GMT) for the first ball of the final session!

Just the start Australia would have wanted in this mini session. They have managed to pick up a wicket but importantly, kept the minds of the English batters clouded, making them circumspect. England will be unhappy with the wicket of Hameed but looking at the positive, Burns has got a start and is forging a partnership with Malan. The tourists will hope for more of the same.
Length and on off, blocked out solidly. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 4.

A loud appeal for LBW but the umpire turns it down! Good length, outside off, this one nips back in sharply. Malan is stuck insde the crease and gets hit high on his pads, as he misses his defense. Jhye Richardson and the group behind the stumps appeal loudly but the umpire isn't interested. Steven Smith comes across and has a word with the bowler. A lot of details get exchanged in jusyt roughly 15 seconds and Smith does not take the review as the last the bowler says is it might to going above the stumps. The replays later confirm that the ball was going way over the stumps.
Amazing work from Green! On a length, outside off. Malan guides it to the left of gully. Green dives to that side and makes a sharp stop.
Good length and wide outside off. Malan has not shot to offer.
Back of a length, just outside off. Malan leaves it alone for the keeper.
Dawid Malan trusting the bounce here. Good-length, outside off, nips in a long way but with some extra bounce this time. Malan shoulders his arms to it.

Touch short, outside off. Burns get across to defend it out.
Good-length ball, around off. Rory Burns shoulders arms to that one.
FOUR! Up and over! Back of a length, wide outside off. Burns upper cuts it over gully and bags a boundary. This should help Burns with his confidence.
Full and on the pads, Burns flicks it to short mid on.

Malan wanted the single but Burns was not interested. The fielder charges towards the ball and looks to throw it at the non-striker's but he slips and goes down on the ground. This allows Malan to get back insde the crease.
Good length and outside off. Malan shoulders his arms to it.
Back of a length, outside off. Malan leaves it for the keeper.
Full length and on off. Burns drives it towards long off. They take three before the fielder cuts it out. It was a good looking shot from Burns.
Good length, on off. Burns defends it out solidly.
Gets beaten this time! Length, around leg, angles across the left-hander. Burns looks to flicks it away but misses and gets hit on his thighs.

Length and outside off, Malan leaves it alone watchfully.
BEAUTY! On a length, outside off., nips away a shade. Malan looks to defend it out but misses and gets beaten on the outside edge.
Good length and outside off. Malan leaves it alone for the keeper.
Good length, around off, nips in a touch again. Malan gets an inside edge onto the pads.

Short and on off. Burns stays back and punches it to point for a single.
Back of a length, outside off, some extra bounce this time. Malan defends it towards gully awkwardly.

The crowd is backing the players here! A loud roar of out goes through the Adelaide Oval but the umpire is unmoved! Back of a length, around middle and leg. OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Yet again, England lose an early wicket. However, this time, you cannot fault the batsman much. This was just perfect, just perfect from Jhye Richardson. Hameed did everything possibly right that he could. It was landed on a length, outside off and Haseeb, rightfully, went forward to defend. But the ball just landed and kept on rising. Now, if that happens, no batsman in the world can control what is going to happen next. It would have been a bad shot had the outside edge been taken. That time, you could fault his technique. But here, the ball has climbed steeply, pinged the gloves and then gone to Alex Carey. So if you are Hameed, just nod your head to Jhye, admiring his delivery. Not your mistake at all. Tough, tough luck.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Carey b Jhye Richardson
